<HEAD>Powerful Storm Rips Central Illinois, Snarls Air Traffic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A fast-moving storm raked central and northern <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> with hail and high winds on Monday, delaying hundreds of flights at <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> airports, and forcing the evacuation of two schools and a factory near <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION>. The storm forced delays of 225 jetliners flying into and out of <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, the nation's busiest, said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Handschiegel </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. `` The average delay was an hour and 15 minutes and the maximum was three hours,'' he said. Flights also were delayed at Midway airport as a tornado watch was issued for the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> area Monday afternoon. A water spout was reported on <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> about 2 p.m., weather service officials said, but it caused no damage. The storm, caused by a collision between a warm front from the south and a cold front from the north, was headed east, weather officials said. <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> was expecting mostly sunny skies Tuesday, with highs in the 50s and 60s. Five people were reported struck by lightning in the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> area, and one, an electrician, remained hospitalized in stable condition Monday night. In <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, the storm unleashed wind gusts up to 63 mph and golf-ball-sized hail, causing extensive damage to buildings, homes and several schools Monday morning. `` We got no warning, no sirens, no nothing,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Collier </PERSON>, school superintendent at <LOCATION> Dunlap </LOCATION>, about six miles northwest of <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION>. `` It was a freak storm that blew up out of nowhere. I was sitting here at my window and I saw it get dark. `` Within about 15 seconds it was really blowing and there was a tremendous electrical storm. Car windows were popping out and exploding, glass was breaking and trees and power lines went down.'' Youngsters at the five <PERSON> Dunlap </PERSON> school buildings were unscathed, although the 500 high school students were ushered outside and classes canceled when officials smelled smoke and feared a fire. Officials found roof damage but no fire. The <ORGANIZATION> Mossville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, about 15 miles east of <LOCATION> Dunlap </LOCATION>, also was closed because of roof damage. Assembly lines were shut down for about 30 minutes and employees were evacuated from shops at <ORGANIZATION> Caterpillar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Mossville </LOCATION> engine plant in a complex that employs about 5,000 people, said <PERSON> Gil </PERSON> <PERSON> Nolde </PERSON>, company spokesman.
