<HEAD>Italy Asks Widow of Nazi Criminal to Stay Away</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds 4 grafs on senators asking about government action,
possible legal penalties</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s justice minister on Monday urged the widow of a Nazi war criminal not to come to <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> to promote a book on how she helped her husband escape from a <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> military prison in 1977. <PERSON> Giuliano </PERSON> <PERSON> Vassalli </PERSON> said that such a visit solely for publicity `` is the cause of legitimate concern'' by relatives of those killed in a massacre for which <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Kappler </PERSON> was judged responsibile. <PERSON> Kappler </PERSON>, an SS colonel in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> during World War II, was sentenced to life in prison for his role in the massacre of 335 Italians in 1944. He escaped in August 1977, reportedly concealed in a large suitcase wheeled out of the prison by his wife. <PERSON> Kappler </PERSON> died of cancer a year later in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. His widow, <PERSON> Annelise </PERSON>, said last week she would come to <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> Saturday to present her book `` I Will Bring You Home.'' A <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said <PERSON> Vassalli </PERSON> issued a statement in response to a letter he received from Mrs. <PERSON> Kappler </PERSON> in which she stated why she planned to come to <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and asked his opinion. Three senators representing <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s largest political parties, the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION>, Communists and Socialists, asked the government Monday to declare what measures it would take to keep Mrs. <PERSON> Kappler </PERSON> out of the country. But the government did not say immediately if it might take legal action. Law provides a prison term of up to 10 years for aiding the escape of a convict sentenced to life.
