<HEAD>Bush Criticizes Dukakis on Military</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with report on advertising expenditures,
anti-Dukakis ad, INSERT two grafs after 11th pvs, Bush was...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Monday accused Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> of a `` total lack of understanding of our military'' and called the Nov. 8 election a referendum on military policy. The vice president used a <ORGANIZATION> Martin-Marietta </ORGANIZATION> defense plant, where `` Star Wars'' research is being conducted, to launch his latest attack on <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. `` I will not leave <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> defenseless against ballistic missiles,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told about 2,500 company employees in the cavernous assembly plant where Titan IV rockets are built. The vice president made the comments before flying to <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, where he addressed a Jewish group at the Holocaust Memorial in <LOCATION> Skokie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told his audience that `` the relationship between <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has never been better, never been stronger. At the <ORGANIZATION> Martin-Marietta </ORGANIZATION> plant, in the foothills of the <LOCATION> Rocky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> ridiculed <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> for opposing continued ballistic missile flight testing. `` We need to modernize. We need to test. And we ca n't defend <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> with blueprints,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. And he scoffed at the Democrat's position on the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's Strategic Defense Initiative, or `` Star Wars,'' program. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has been highly critical of the proposed system _ designed to destroy incoming <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> missiles in space _ but has also said during the campaign that he might support some continued research. Noting that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> had once called the program a fantasy, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> asked: `` Why spend a dime, if you think it's a fantasy?'' Attacking <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> for his opposition to new missile systems and for his emphasis on stronger conventional forces has been a main <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign theme. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was planning to introduce that theme in an ad using footage of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> riding around in a tank during a campaign visit to <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, said campaign spokeswoman <PERSON> Sheila </PERSON> <PERSON> Tate </PERSON>. Although Ms. <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> had no information on a <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> report Tuesay that the campaign was tentatively planning to spend more than $ 15 million of its $ 30 million-plus advertising in three states, she said three new ads were being aired Tuesday, and a new ad was being shot then. The three states are <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> declared on Monday that with the next century approaching, `` it is all that more important for us to understand the role that our defense has played in securing the peace, the role our military forces must continue to play if <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s future is also to be secure. `` And this election is a referendum about that role.'' At <LOCATION> Skokie </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> stood in a violent thunderstorm at an outdoor rally for the dedication, where he said: `` I am committed to the survival of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has survived, will survive, has flourished, will flourish.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> talked about the importance of maintaining the `` strategic relationship'' with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and joked: `` I wish that the Lord had given us a little bit of a different weather condition. He works in strange and mysterious ways.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> did not mention the controversial effort by the American <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> to hold a march in <LOCATION> Skokie </LOCATION> in 1978 in which the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> were represented by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> decided at the last minute to hold their march in neighboring <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has frequently criticized <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> for his membership in the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION>. Aides said the visit should be viewed reinforcement of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s criticism With polls showing the vice president pulling ahead of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> _ including an <ORGANIZATION> NBC-Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> poll Monday showing <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> ahead 55-38 _ Republican strategists say <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will focus on a few proven-effective themes such as defense in the remaining three weeks before the election. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> donned a bright blue work jacket as he toured the <ORGANIZATION> Martin-Marietta </ORGANIZATION> plant, accompanied by <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlesinger </PERSON>, who has served in Cabinet jobs in both Democratic and Republican administrations. The vice president was shown a simulator for a laser weapon system to be based on an orbiting space station called `` Rapid Retargeting, Precision Pointing,'' or by its facetious code name, `` R2P2.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was told by <ORGANIZATION> Martin-Marietta </ORGANIZATION> vice president <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thorson </PERSON> that the device was so accurate that it could hit a basketball on top of the Empire State Building in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> from <PERSON> Pike </PERSON>'s Peak in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Schlesinger </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> defense </ORGANIZATION> secretary and <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> director for President <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and energy secretary for President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, told the plant employees that `` the presidency is no place for on-the-job training.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said that the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor's refusal to back new nuclear systems and his willingness to cut two aircraft carriers `` indicates his total lack of understanding of our military.'' `` Governor, it's time to stop running down our defenses,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. Meanwhile, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he favors a `` possible mix'' for a new generation of mobile intercontinental ballistic missiles between the Midgetman missile and a rail-based MX missile system _ but not full deployment of both. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s foreign policy adviser, said going ahead with both weapons systems would cost some $ 60 billion, and that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wanted to keep the costs of the program to about half that.
