<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the modern age of presidential politics, the Democrats have a lot of experience being given up for dead. Generally, it's been a realistic enough presentiment, but <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> will surely look for inspiration to several remarkable party heroes. <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hubert </PERSON> <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON> are the Mr. Octobers of their era. It was probably <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> foe <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Dewey </PERSON> whom <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> front-runner <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was thinking about when he vowed over the weekend to `` go the extra mile'' this month, and added, `` I'm not going to mess up.'' <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> was using <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON> as his weekend role models. `` Our party has a proud tradition of closing from behind,'' said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' indefatigable running mate. He told a farmer's market in <LOCATION> St </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, `` I ca n't help but remember <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> out there when the press had written him off.'' <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON> came up short, of course, but his 1968 October comeback was still extraordinary, following as it did a divisive primary campaign and a calamitous convention. He sought to succeed an unpopular president _ <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> _ for whom the word albatross comes to mind. But come back he did. After finally staking out some independence from <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON> put together a high-energy campaign in October and ended with 42.7 percent of the vote, nearly scaring <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> out of his wits. -LRB- <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> ended with 43.4 percent. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> had 13.5 percent -RRB-. Though a sitting president in 1948, <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> did n't win nomination until well after midnight, at which time convention managers released a flock of doves to celebrate. The doves, stifled by the heat, promptly dropped dead on the convention floor, prompting one party stalwart to reflect, `` Dead pigeons, just like <PERSON> Truman </PERSON>.'' Except the year did n't end with <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> dead. Unpopular and far behind in the polls, <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> invented the whistlestop, making an average of 10 speeches a day from the back of a train and sparing the Republicans no ridicule in that blunt, partisan `` Give ` Em Hell'' manner of his. <PERSON> Dewey </PERSON> was no <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>; he stayed above the fray. On election day, <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> stood expectations on their head, winning 49.5 percent of the vote to <PERSON> Dewey </PERSON>'s 45 percent. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> enjoys the same mid-October expectations as <PERSON> Truman </PERSON>, which is to say few outside his immediate family really believe he'll win. But there are differences between the two men, and one is half-tempted to look over at the cerebral and aloof <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and say, `` Governor, you're no <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Truman </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> never had to say, `` I think I'm a reasonably likable guy,'' and if you asked him to name his heroes in American life, can you imagine <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> responding _ as did <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> last Thursday night _ `` Some of them are in public life, in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, some of my fellow governors ... are real heroes to me.'' His fellow governors! <PERSON> Truman </PERSON>, like <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, was not a commanding figure. Lots of people looked down upon him, figuratively and literally. `` At first the critics referred to my -LRB- campaign -RRB- tour as a ` one-man circus,' and called it less efficient and less dignified than the campaign being put on by the Republicans,'' <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> said in his memoirs, describing his comeback this way: `` I simply told the people in my own language that they had better wake up to the fact that it was their fight. If they did not get out and help me win this fight, I emphasized, the Republicans would soon be giving the farmers and the workers the little end of the stick again.'' The <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> command huddled in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> and emerged to tell <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> they would, a la Truman, concentrate on economic themes in the last-ditch drive for a miracle. They mapped out an effort to concentrate on 18 states with 272 electoral votes. That does n't leave any margin for error. It takes 270 electoral votes to win the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, and common sense says you ca n't win every state you contest _ unless you're <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and you're going to win them all anyway By Sunday, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> had merged his Truman reminisces with a World Series theme, buoyed by the fact that the underdogs from <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> had won a first-game victory with the gimpy <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON>'s two-out homer in ninth `` We're going to be like the <ORGANIZATION> Dodgers </ORGANIZATION> last night,'' he said. `` It looked like they were down and out and all of a sudden they hit a home run and won it. And I think we can do that in the next 24 days.'' Of course this is <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> talking, not <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>.
