 ago, while the state needs a 8.3 percent annual rate to balance the budget. But the first quarter results were affected by a $ 68 million payout in corporate abatements stemming from a tax break the Legislature has now closed. The <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> administration contends revenues will rebound this year through a variety of new specialized tax increases, such as levying the sales tax on cigarettes; increased tax auditing practices and ending certain tax breaks. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Manley </PERSON>, president of the non-partisan <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Taxpayers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION>, is not so confident. The foundation estimates a shortfall of $ 180 million to $ 220 million. However, <PERSON> Manley </PERSON> said that is manageable if the administration demonstrates the same discipline it showed in fiscal 1988. The budget problems the state faced in the past fiscal year resulted mainly from unexpected changes in taxpayer behavior due to federal tax law changes, particularly affecting capital gains. As a result, final revenue growth for the year was 2.1 percent compared to a budget expectation of 6.6 percent. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was able to balance the books on fiscal 1988 principally through the largest planned reduction in spending ever attempted in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>. Some $ 233 million was systematically trimmed, primarily by delaying the start of new programs. The policy caused disappointment among advocates but little reduction in existing services. The administration also shifted about $ 185 million in construction projects scheduled to be paid from general funds to long-term bonds. In the fiscal 1989 budget, which <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> proposed in January before all of the problems surfaced in fiscal 1988, he cut about $ 200 million in new and expanded programs while the Legislature was still debating the bill and vetoed or delayed spending over $ 200 million more when he signed it into law. He also won passage of several new revenue sources: the $ 33.7 million cigarette sales tax; $ 75 million from income tax updating; $ 180 million from new tax enforcement; and $ 40 million from corporate tax changes. In 1975, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> inherited a deficit that slowly grew to $ 560 million out of a budget of $ 3.8 billion. It forced him to slash spending for general relief and state employee pay raises and finally to sign an income surtax, the biggest broad-based tax in the state's history. The actions contributed to his defeat four years later and gave <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> the basis to label him a tax-raiser. Re-entering the governor's office in 1983, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> inherited another deficit projected to reach $ 300 million. This time, <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> legislators urged him to go for another big tax increase, but instead he pushed for smaller spending cutbacks and a major crackdown on uncollected taxes. The year ended with a $ 41 million surplus.
