<HEAD>With South African Troops Gone, UNITA Finds New Friends</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW TORCHIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MAVINGA, Angola (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With South African troops out of southern <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, rebel leader <PERSON> Jonas </PERSON> <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> says his <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas face a tougher military struggle but have gained support in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Guerrilla officers promise few prolonged battles of the kind that <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> and South African forces waged early this year in the siege of Cuito Cuanavale. Angolan government units were temporarily driven out of the southern town, they say. But, eight months later, <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> is back in defensive positions east of Cuito, awaiting an enemy campaign. The departure of several thousand <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> African </LOCATION> soldiers seven weeks ago, as part of regional peace negotiations, `` has weakened our position,'' <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> said in a recent interview. But he said the South African move has bolstered <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION>'s credibility as an independent force and has increased diplomatic pressure on the Angolan government to negotiate a settlement The declared goal of <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> _ the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Total </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Independence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angola </ORGANIZATION> _ is to force the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Popular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Independence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angola </ORGANIZATION> into a power-sharing arrangement leading to national elections. <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> expressed confidence that <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION>, relying on traditional guerrilla advantages of speed and surprise, can maintain the stalemate in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>'s 13-year civil war. `` We can not come out without wounds. But we can sustain some wounds,'' <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> said. `` For sure, <PERSON> Jamba </PERSON> will never fall,'' <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> said, referring to <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> bush </PERSON> headquarters in southeastern <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. `` They will pay such a heavy price _ I think they will not try.'' <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> says it has 37,000 guerrillas and 28,000 regular soldiers, nearly half as many as the government's more heavily armed 80,000 soldiers and the 50,000 Cuban troops on its side. Negotiations involving <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> are aimed at an agreement by Nov. 1 for a <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> withdrawal. In return, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> would allow implementation of a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> independence plan for <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, also known as <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. The Marxist Angolan government `` can not stand alone without the Cubans,'' <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> said during the interview at an unmapped forest supply camp near <LOCATION> Mavinga </LOCATION>, about 80 miles from forward <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> positions. `` African countries are giving much more sympathy since the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africans </LOCATION> left,'' <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> said. He named <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Togo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Senegal </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cameroon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chad </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guinea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mali </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> as sympathetic to <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION>'s cause. He said liberal <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Democrats, Sens. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, told him during a visit to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> this year that the main barrier to their understanding `` was the direct involvement of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>.'' `` Now we are working very well,'' he said of the Democrats. Brig. <PERSON> Peregrino </PERSON> <PERSON> Chindondo </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION>'s intelligence chief, said guerrillas caused serious Cuban casualties and burned eight Cuban vehicles in a raid Oct. 6 on a convoy near the central highlands city of <LOCATION> Huambo </LOCATION>. He said 25 vehicles were seized Oct. 3 when <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> took <PERSON> Sanzo </PERSON> <PERSON> Pombo </PERSON> in the northern <LOCATION> Uige </LOCATION> Province. `` The morale of the enemy is very bad,'' <PERSON> Chindondo </PERSON> said. `` Most are recruited in round-up operations. There is friction with the Cubans. They have lost the support of the people.'' During an 11-day tour of <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> bases in southeastern <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, where the movement effectively governs one-third of the country, reporters visited a guerrilla command post 3 miles from enemy lines at Cuito Cuanavale. There they talked with Angolan prisoner of war <PERSON> Julio </PERSON> <PERSON> Wango </PERSON>, 25, a few hours after he was captured in a skirmish. Wounds on Wango's head and elbows were bandaged. He was barefoot and <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> officers said it was customary to remove prisoners' boots so they could not escape. <PERSON> Wango </PERSON> said he had fled his village near <LOCATION> Ganda </LOCATION>, in <LOCATION> Benguela </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Province </LOCATION>, to avoid military service but was caught by a government squad in a cornfield in March. `` They beat me and told me I was a crook for trying to escape,'' Wango said. `` They gave me three months' training and made me a sergeant.'' `` In the army, we do n't have any food, no breakfast. People are weak and fall while on duty,'' Wango said. `` The only ones getting good food are Cubans. `` Once I ran away to another brigade to trade beads for something to eat. They found me and put me in confinement for five days.''
