<HEAD>Brawl Erupts Between Americans And Koreans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 40 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> soldiers brandishing jacknives and broken bottles brawled with rock-throwing <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Koreans </LOCATION> in the capital's shopping district. An <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> and a South Korean were hospitalized, officials said today. News reports said one American and three Koreans were injured in the clash early Sunday, and one of the Koreans was in critical condition. According to a military press release, the incident in the nightclub section of Itaewon was sparked by a verbal altercation between a Korean taxi driver and an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> soldier. The argument escalated into an assault involving four Americans and a number of Koreans. Itaewon is a a shopping district close to the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Forces Korea Headquarters in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>. South Korean police officials said the four Americans suddenly began cursing at the taxi driver, <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Ok-Chul </PERSON>, 51, and kicked his cab on a street corner. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> was quoted as saying that when he got of his car and protested, the Americans punched him in the face and some even climbed on top of his car. The officials said about 40 Koreans rushed to <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>'s aid. The Americans then fled, brandishing empty beer bottles and throwing rocks at the pursuing crowd. When Korean passers-by jeered at the fleeing Americans, police said about 40 other <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> soldiers joined in and brandished jack knives and broken beer bottle at the Koreans, who countered by throwing rocks. The Koreans, whose number had swelled to about 200 by then, shouted `` Yankee go home,'' in front of a nightclub into which the Americans had fled, the officials said. About 200 police who arrived at the scene dispersed the crowd of Koreans. The four unidentified soldiers involved in the initial altercation were booked for investigation and turned over to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> miltiary authorities, the police said. Officials did not release the names of the injured and it was not immediately clear when the injuries occurred.
