<HEAD>Hirohito Discharges More Blood, Court Festival Held</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> discharged more blood today but his condition remains stable, officials said. The crown prince and other members of the imperial family meanwhile attended an annual harvest festival. <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>, 87, discharged a small amount of blood `` on several occasions'' Sunday night through this morning, <ORGANIZATION> Imperial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Household </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Kenji </PERSON> <PERSON> Maeda </PERSON> told palace reporters. The world's longest-reigning monarch, who has discharged small amounts of blood since Saturday, was given a transfusion of 0.84 pints of blood Sunday, bringing the total he has received since vomiting blood Sept. 19 to 17.4 pints. The transfusions were administered to help the emperor combat anemia and supplement blood lost in internal bleeding, according to palace officials. The rite, called Kannamesai, includes offering prayers in the direction of the Ise Shrine, where the sun goddess is worshipped, and presenting sacred offerings at a small shrine on the palace grounds, according to palace spokesman <PERSON> Chifuru </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashizawa </PERSON>. `` The Kannamesai is an imperial festival giving thanks to the gods by offering newly harvested crops,'' <PERSON> Ashizawa </PERSON> said.
