<HEAD>Nicaraguan Government Campaigns Against Church Leader</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government appears to be on a campaign to discredit the head of the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, Cardinal <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Obando </PERSON> y Bravo, over the church's use of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> funds. But the main issue seems to be the government's determination, now that it feels it has defeated the U.S.-backed rebels militarily, to stop the flow of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> funds to groups opposed to or not supportive of the leftist Sandinista regime. Conservative estimates by political opposition sources in the capital <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> say more than $ 50,000 arrive from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> monthly. The Sandinistas argue that most of the money comes from the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> even if it is distributed by labor, church or other groups. On Saturday, President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> accused <PERSON> Obando </PERSON> y Bravo and Nicaraguan bishops of becoming `` instruments of <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s politics of death'' by accepting <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> funds At the center of the controversy with the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> is the role of the cardinal as one of the two members of the <ORGANIZATION> Verification </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> agreed upon by the Sandinista government and the rebels, known as Contras. The duty of the commission is to confirm that the two sides are following the peace accords tentatively approved earlier this year. The other commission member is <PERSON> Joao </PERSON> <PERSON> Baena </PERSON> <PERSON> Soares </PERSON>, secretary-general of the Organization of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, or OAS. The tentative peace accords specified that <ORGANIZATION> Verification </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> would be under the control of <PERSON> Baena </PERSON> <PERSON> Soares </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> OAS </ORGANIZATION> would pay for expenses, but to speed things up the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Agency for 1nternational Development agreed to provide the $ 10 million needed. <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Curia </LOCATION> spokesman Monsignor <PERSON> Bismark </PERSON> <PERSON> Carballo </PERSON> explained that nearly $ 1 million of the funds would be used by the church to acquire equipment and pay salaries of members of local verification commissionss set up by the church in cease-fire areas. The issue came to light a few days ago when the government-controlled news media accused <PERSON> Obando </PERSON> y Bravo of trying to bring in, duty-free, 17 four-wheel vehicles and a similar number of generators reportedly to be used by the local verification commissions. Assistant Foreign Minister <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> <PERSON> Tinoco </PERSON> said there is nothing the local commissions can verify since there was no concrete agreement between the government and the Contras. `` What are they verifying?'' <PERSON> Tinoco </PERSON> asked last week, adding the gpvernment does not recognize the cardinal as being in charge of the <ORGANIZATION> Verification </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. According to the original accords, the commission would verify the movement of the Contras into safe cease-fire areas, withdrawal of Sandinista troops and the eventual disarming of the rebels and their return to civilian life. The talks broke down in June, with both sides announcing unilateral cease-fires. The local verification commissions were to be made up of the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> bishops in the cease-fire areas and people they appointed as well as foreign representatives named by the <ORGANIZATION> OAS </ORGANIZATION> secretary-general. <PERSON> Baena </PERSON> <PERSON> Soares </PERSON> has remained quiet during the controversy, and currently the commissions have only those members named by the church. Church officials say they feel the commissions are also charged with verification of respect for human rights and `` democratization'' in the cease-fire areas. `` We know what they are doing,'' <PERSON> Tinoco </PERSON> said. Church officials acknowledge the commissions have gathered information harmful to the government. <PERSON> Tinoco </PERSON> said any funds for the <ORGANIZATION> Verification </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> `` may be suspended until the government and the commission reach an agreement on the way the commissions will work.'' Church officials said privately they feel the government may be trying to force <PERSON> Obando </PERSON> y Bravo to step down as a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Verification </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. The cardinal angered the government Oct. 9 when he publicly criticized it for rejecting humanitarian aid approved by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>.
