<HEAD>Extradition Hearings To Begin For Accused California Mass Murderer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man wanted in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> for allegedly carrying out a string of sex slayings wo n't be returning to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> soon even though he faces extradition proceedings, his lawyer has predicted. Hearings will begin today to determine whether <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Ng </PERSON>, currently serving a 4 -LCB- - year jail sentence here for armed robbery, should be extradited to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> But <PERSON> Ng </PERSON>'s Calgary-based lawyer, <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> MacLeod </PERSON>, said it could be a long time before his 27-year-old client heads south. If <PERSON> Ng </PERSON> loses the case, there will likely be an appeal, he said. <PERSON> Ng </PERSON> was convicted in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> in December 1985 after a botched shoplifting attempt in <LOCATION> Calgary </LOCATION> in which a security guard was shot in the hand. But the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> wants Ng back to face 25 felony counts in <LOCATION> Calfornia </LOCATION>, including the murders of 12 people. Eleven of the deaths involved grisly sex slayings at a rural cabin in <LOCATION> Calaveras </LOCATION> <LOCATION> county </LOCATION>, 120 miles east of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. The other murder case involves the death of a <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> disc jockey, and other charges include burglary, kidnapping and false imprisonment. Ng, a native of <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and a former marine, came to <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> after his companion, <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lake </PERSON>, was picked up for shoplifting in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> and committed suicide. <PERSON> Lake </PERSON> later was linked to the deaths or disappearances of 22 people. That investigation led to the charges against <PERSON> Ng </PERSON>. If extradited and convicted, Ng faces possible execution in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> has a policy against extraditing anyone facing the death penalty, but the final decision will ultimately rest with <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> Minister <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Hnatyshyn </PERSON>. The hearings, which are being held to determine if there is enough evidence to send <PERSON> Ng </PERSON> back to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, are expected to last up to five weeks. Not all evidence will be available to the public. Madame Justice <PERSON> Marguerite </PERSON> <PERSON> Trussler </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Alberta </LOCATION>'s Court of Queen's Bench ordered in May that anything said in open court could be reported but the courtroom would be cleared when certain sensitive material was discussed. Among observers at the hearings will be some family members of <PERSON> Ng </PERSON>'s alleged victims, who were given financial aid by the Edmonton-based Victims of Violence for their trip. <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON> <PERSON> Sellitto </PERSON>, whose 39-year-old brother <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Cosner </PERSON> is one of <PERSON> Ng </PERSON>'s alleged victims, said she wanted to see the accused killer for herself. `` I want to hate him in person,'' <PERSON> Sellitto </PERSON> said recently from her <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> home. She plans to attend the hearings. Allegations of torture and mass murder in the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> deaths have caused many to question <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s extradition procedure. As recently as May, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Deukmejian </PERSON> urged Prime Minister <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> to speed up the process. In a letter, <PERSON> Deukmejian </PERSON> said denying the extradition `` could have the unfortunate consequence of making <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> a haven for death penalty fugitives.'' But <PERSON> Ng </PERSON>'s Calgary-based lawyer, <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> MacLeod </PERSON>, predicted it could be a long time before Ng heads south. Regardless of the outcome of the extradition hearings, he said, there will likely be an appeal.
