 Unseasonably heavy rains flooded much of western <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, forced about 45 people to be evacuated from homes and campgrounds, and stranded two hikers shivering under a tree for a night. `` We had just about lost hope. We thought we were going to die out there,'' said <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Winsel </PERSON>, 28, of <LOCATION> Fairfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, who was hiking with his 30-year-old brother, <PERSON> Mike </PERSON>, of <PERSON> Everett </PERSON>. Rain tapered off and floodwaters were receding late Sunday in the <LOCATION> Cascade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION> foothills east of <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, but more rain was predicted for tonight and early Tuesday with the approach of another storm system, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said. The Winsels were trapped in the <LOCATION> Vesper </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peak </LOCATION> area about 20 miles south of <LOCATION> Sultan </LOCATION>, a town of 1,500 residents 30 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>. The brothers were dressed in boots and jackets and had some food, but said it was icy cold and only one of them had gloves. `` We were awake all night shivering,'' <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Winsel </PERSON> said. `` In the morning, we tried to return on the logging road, but we found the -LRB- <LOCATION> Skykomish </LOCATION> -RRB- river had risen overnight and had wiped out the road in three places.'' The only bridge they found was impassable, so the brothers had to swim across the river, where they were picked up by a truck driver and taken back to <PERSON> Sultan </PERSON>. `` We probably would n't have been able to survive if we'd have stayed outdoors another night,'' <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Winsel </PERSON> said. `` We'd already spent 24 hours in hell.'' The Skykomish crested in Sultan on Sunday three feet above flood stage, Fire Chief <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Knowlton </PERSON> said. About 15 residents had to be evacuated by boat from the town Sunday morning, according to <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Christian </PERSON>, a dispatch supervisor for the <LOCATION> Snohomish </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> sheriff's office. Residents were allowed to return home Sunday night. <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> volunteers fed 30 people and arranged for emergency housing after evacuating them from trailers in the <LOCATION> Snoqualmie </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Campground </LOCATION> on Sunday, said relief worker <PERSON> Hope </PERSON> <PERSON> Tuttle </PERSON>. The contents of two or three trailers were believed destroyed, she said. The Skagit and Stillaguamish rivers also reached flood stage at upper elevations Sunday, the weather service reported. A flood warning for the <LOCATION> Nooksack </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> was canceled late Sunday. The floodwaters closed numerous roads throughout the Cascade foothills. No damage estimate was immediately available. Heavy rain washed enough logging debris down the <LOCATION> Skagit </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> to cause a partial dam to form at a <LOCATION> Burlington </LOCATION> Northern railroad bridge, but no major problems were anticipated, said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheahan </PERSON>, management director of the <ORGANIZATION> Skagit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>. During the 48 hours ending at 5 p.m. Sunday, the weather service reported 1.64 inches of rain in <LOCATION> Bellingham </LOCATION>, 1.39 in <LOCATION> Olympia </LOCATION>, 1.04 at <LOCATION> Seattle-Tacoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airp