<HEAD>Pro-Government Press Hails Botha's Trip As Breakthrough</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pro-government newspapers today hailed President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s trip to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> as a rousing success although no agreements were announced and <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> declined to divulge details. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> returned Sunday following a 10-day trip, the latest in a series of foreign journeys aimed at easing the country's diplomatic isolation. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> attended the funeral of Bavarian governor <PERSON> Franz </PERSON> <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON> in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, then went to <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> where he met with bankers and businessmen. En route back to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> stopped briefly Saturday in <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> met with Prime Minister <PERSON> Anibal </PERSON> <PERSON> Cavaco </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON>, and in the <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> with President <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Houphouet-Boigny </PERSON>. According to the French news agency Agence France-Presse, <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> made a brief statement in the <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, saying his conversations with Houphouet covered African problems in general and southern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> in particular, but he did not elaborate. `` It is always a privilege to meet him,'' <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> said of Houphouet according to the AFP report. `` We did n't want to pass by without stopping in this country of goodwill.'' None of the officials who met <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> have issued public statements regarding the talks. The <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> stopover marked <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s fourth visit to a black-ruled African country since mid-September. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> declined to discuss the specifics of his talks with <PERSON> Houphouet-Boigny </PERSON>, one of <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s longest-serving leaders. `` We discussed matters concerning <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and especially southern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. We decided not to make statements,'' <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> said. The Citizen, a pro-government newspaper, said <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s recent travels have focused world attention onto <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. `` At a time when one might have expected the world to demonstrate an obsession with the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> presidential election, the spotlight has instead been turned on <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>,'' the newspaper said today in an editorial. The Afrikaans-language daily <ORGANIZATION> Beeld </ORGANIZATION> said: `` What clearly began as a visit to pay homage to a dead friend -LRB- <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON> -RRB- turned into a noteworthy trip. ... Perhaps these moves could be followed up by one or two dramatic developments internally that will show the world that we are earnest about reform.'' The newspaper suggested the government could release jailed African National Congress leader <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> and scrap pending legislation designed to strengthen the Group Areas Act, which segregates neighborhoods by race. The government-run <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s travels herald a `` fundamental change'' in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s relationship with the rest of the `` By the end of last week even the most hardened cynics were having to concede that a new spirit of conciliation was abroad,'' the <ORGANIZATION> SABC </ORGANIZATION> said. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, who has held power since 1978, never held a summit meeting in a black-ruled African nation until he traveled to <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION> last month. He also has visited <LOCATION> Malawi </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION> in recent weeks. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> says Presidents <PERSON> Joaquim </PERSON> <PERSON> Chissano </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Mobutu </PERSON> Sese Seko of <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION> are likely to visit <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> in coming months. The Citizen, quoting unidentified government officials, said there was a `` possibility'' that <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> would meet with Angolan President <PERSON> Eduardo </PERSON> <PERSON> dos </PERSON> <PERSON> Santos </PERSON>. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> in August withdrew its troops from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, where they fought alongside the anti-Marxist <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> rebels. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, along with <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> mediators, have been attempting to negotiate an agreement on the withdrawal of 50,000 Cuban troops supporting the Angolan government and independence for <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, the territory ruled by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>.
