<BYLINE>By JAMES MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tropical Storm <PERSON> Joan </PERSON>'s winds strengthened to 60 mph today as it skimmed over the <LOCATION> Colombian </LOCATION> peninsula on a westward path back out over the warm waters of the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>, forecasters say. `` This storm has defied what it's supposed to do,'' said <PERSON> Miles </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON>, a forecaster at the National Hurricane Center in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. `` Any storm that passes that close to land should be weakening, not strengthening.'' At 9 a.m. EDT today, <PERSON> Joan </PERSON>'s center was located near latitude 12.0 north and longitude 72.1 west, putting it over the <LOCATION> Guajira </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>. The storm was moving west near 12 mph on a path that would take it over the southwestern <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> later today. Although little additional strengthening was expected today, <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> said the storm could become more powerful during the next day or two as it moved over warm water. <PERSON> Joan </PERSON>, whose winds diminished Sunday to 45 mph, roared back to 60 mph today with gale-force gusts extending 50 miles. Four to 8 inches of rain was recorded along the storm's path. Tropical storm warnings remained in effect for the <LOCATION> Guajira </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Paraguana </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Monjes </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>. Small craft in the area were asked to remain in port. On Tuesday, <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> became the 10th named system of the 1988 <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> hurricane season when top winds passed 39 mph. It would be upgraded to a hurricane if its winds hit 74 mph. There have been four hurricanes during the six-month season that ends Nov. 30. The worst was Hurricane Gilbert