<HEAD>Court to Consider Ohio Retirement Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Associated Press Writer = <LOCATION> WASHINGTON </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today agreed to consider allowing states to give larger retirement benefits to public employees forced to quit work before age 60 The court said it will review a ruling that struck down an <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> pension law provision on grounds it violated a federal law against discrimination based on age. The <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> provision was challenged by <PERSON> June </PERSON> <PERSON> Betts </PERSON>, a former speech pathologist for the <ORGANIZATION> Hamilton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Retardation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. When her work degenerated because of medical problems, Ms. <PERSON> Betts </PERSON> was given a choice by the state in 1985 of taking unpaid medical leave or retirement with a standard pension. She was barred from receiving more generous disability retirement benefits because she was 61. A provision of the state pension plan allowed disability benefits only for those who worked for the state for at least five years and were under 60 when forced to quit. Ms. <PERSON> Betts </PERSON>' pension would have been $ 158.50 a month under the standard plan, compared to $ 355 a month in disability retirement benefits. The 6th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> last June upheld a federal judge's ruling in Ms. <PERSON> Betts </PERSON>' favor that threw out the state's age-based pension provision The appeals court said the provision violated the federal Age Discrimination in Employment Act. The appeals court said the federal law permits age-based benefits only when they `` can be justified by a substantial business purpose.'' <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> officials failed to prove that giving larger benefits to younger workers is justified by cost considerations, the appeals court said. In fact, the appeals court said, such an arrangement might prove more costly to the state since a worker who becomes disabled at a younger age would draw more in benefits over the course of the worker's lifetime than someone disabled at 60 or older. <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> officials argued that the state's age-based provision is permissible because it was adopted prior to enactment of the federal Age Discrimination in Employment Act. The state said federal appeals courts other than the 6th Circuit have agreed with its position. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employees </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Retirement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> vs. <PERSON> Betts </PERSON>, 88-389.
