<HEAD>Reputed Philadelphia-Area Crime Boss Loses Appeal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Reputed Philadelphia-area crime boss <PERSON> Nicodemo </PERSON> <PERSON> Scarfo </PERSON> lost a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> appeal today to overturn his extortion-conspiracy conviction. The court, without comment, rejected arguments that <PERSON> Scarfo </PERSON> did not receive a fair trial. <PERSON> Scarfo </PERSON>, described as the head of organized crime in eastern <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> and parts of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, is serving a 14-year prison term for scheming to extort $ 1 million from a developer of the <LOCATION> Penn </LOCATION>'s Landing redevelopment project on the <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> waterfront. The developer, <ORGANIZATION> Rouse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>, told the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> of the extortion plan that called for it to pay $ 1 million in exchange for backing from <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> city Councilman <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> <PERSON> Beloff </PERSON> for the project. <PERSON> Beloff </PERSON> and his administrative aide, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Rego </PERSON>, were tried separately and convicted in the kickback scheme. <PERSON> Scarfo </PERSON> said he did not receive a fair trial in part because the jurors' names were withheld when they were selected. They were identified only by number. Also, the trial judge in explaining the reason for the anonymity told the jurors he wanted to assure them that they or their families had no reason to fear. `` There will be a lot of testimony concerning organized crime,'' the judge said. `` I have never heard of a case where any defendant ever tried to cause harm to a juror or a member of the juror's family But we all watch television. We all read newspapers. We see the Godfather movies. I wanted to make sure that no member of the jury would worry about it.'' Also, <PERSON> Scarfo </PERSON> said the jury was influenced improperly by testimony about extraneous crimes presented with `` frightening imagery and detail.'' For example, the prosecutor summed up the case by saying <PERSON> Scarfo </PERSON> `` is a shrewd, clever and dangerous man. He rules his criminal army with a deadly iron fist. He keeps his soldiers in mortal fear.'' The 3rd U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> upheld the conviction last July. The appeals court said anonymity for the jurors and the explanation the trial judge gave for the procedure may have helped dispel the jurors' fears and served `` the ideal of dispassionate judgment.'' The appeals court also upheld the use of testimony by mob hit men who testified for the government that they carried out murders at <PERSON> Scarfo </PERSON>'s behest. The prosecution used the testimony to try and prove that the witnesses cooperated with the government for fear they would meet the same fate, the appeals court said. The case is <PERSON> Scarfo </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, 88-498.
