<HEAD>Winner More Disbelieving Than Surprised</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with comment from Hitchings,
picking up 4th graf pvs, `The work...'. INSERTS 2 grafs after 15th
graf, `The drugs...', with further background.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Nobel, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A researcher who shared the Nobel Prize for medicine today said the best reward is still knowing his work has saved lives, while his longtime colleague says she was more disbelieving than anything after journalists gave her the news. `` The phone keeps ringing and I ca n't seem to finish getting dressed or anything else,'' said <PERSON> Gertrude </PERSON> <PERSON> Elion </PERSON>, a researcher at <ORGANIZATION> Burroughs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wellcome </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> since 1944, from her home in <LOCATION> Chapel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>. `` I think I'm going to have trouble getting to work on time.'' <PERSON> Elion </PERSON>, 70; <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitchings </PERSON>, 83, another longtime Wellcome researcher; and a British scientist shared the award and will split a prize worth $ 390,000. `` It's wonderful for my descendents,'' joked <PERSON> Hitchings </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Burroughs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wellcome </ORGANIZATION> vice president. `` I've had many awards, but my real awards have come from patients whose lives have been saved by the drugs I've invented.'' The work of <PERSON> Elion </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hitchings </PERSON> led to a series of drugs for the treatment of cancer and a variety of other diseases. <ORGANIZATION> Burroughs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wellcome </ORGANIZATION> is a major pharmaceutical company. <PERSON> Elion </PERSON> said she first got the news at 6:30 a.m. from a reporter and had not yet heard from Nobel officials. `` Surprised is not exactly the word,'' she said, when asked her reaction to the prize. `` Disbelieving is the right word. As I say, I have n't heard from the Nobel people, and until they confirm it, I wo n't believe it. I did not even know I had been nominated for it.'' She said a reporter had read her parts of the citation, `` but it was fairly vague. I do n't even know exactly what the award is for at this point.'' She said she had collaborated with <PERSON> Hitchings </PERSON> for more than 40 years. `` That's why it's so surprising when something like this happens after so many years,'' she said. `` I have n't been able to use the phone to call him,'' she said of <PERSON> Hitchings </PERSON>. `` But other people who have called have told me they talked to him, so I know he knows about it. I think I'll have to go use a phone somewhere else, but first I've got to run a comb through my hair.'' <PERSON> Hitchings </PERSON>, who was born in <LOCATION> Hoquiam </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, received a doctorate in biochemistry from <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> in 1933 and holds more than 80 American patents. He joined <ORGANIZATION> Burroughs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wellcome </ORGANIZATION> in 1942 as a biochemist and retired in 1975 as vice president for research. <PERSON> Elion </PERSON>, a native of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, received a bachelor's degree from <ORGANIZATION> Hunter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in 1937, and a master's degree in chemistry from <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in 1941. She joined <ORGANIZATION> Burroughs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wellcome </ORGANIZATION> in 1944 as a biochemist. In 1967, she was appointed head of the department of experimental therapy, a position she held until her retirment in 1983. <PERSON> Hitchings </PERSON> and <PERSON> Elion </PERSON> followed a line of nucleic acid research that led to the discovery of new drugs for malaria, leukemia, gout, bacterial infections and the first immune suppressant to make kidney transplants possible, the company said. The drugs developed by the two scientists include Imuran, for kidney transplants; <PERSON> Purinethol </PERSON>, a cancer drug used to treat leukemia patients; Zyloprim, for gout; and Zovirax, the first drug developed for the treatment of herpes virus infections, said <ORGANIZATION> Burroughs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wellcome </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Bartlett </PERSON>. The researchers hold the title of scientist emeritus at <ORGANIZATION> Burroughs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wellcome </ORGANIZATION>, signifying that they are retired. Despite their retirement, both have continued to work on projects, said another company spokesman, <PERSON> Thack </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>. `` Both of them still come to work every day,'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said. `` They both have their own research projects, but they were so involved in so many things that were going on in research that they're still consulted.'' This is the third Nobel Prize for <ORGANIZATION> Burroughs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wellcome </ORGANIZATION>, Ms. <PERSON> Bartlett </PERSON> said. In 1936, Sir <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Dale </PERSON>, an early director of research and chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Wellcome </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION>, was awarded a Nobel in medicine for his studies of chemical transmission of nerve impulses. In 1982, Sir <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Vane </PERSON>, group research and development director, won a Nobel in medicine for his role in discovering the way in which aspirin works to reduce pain and inflammation.
