<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An Afghan guerrilla leader said today the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> wants direct talks with the Moslem forces fighting the Moscow-backed Afghan government. Official Afghan radio said troops killed two Americans who were helping guerrillas. `` The green lights have been shown'' for direct negotiations, said <PERSON> Burhanuddin </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabbani </PERSON>, current chairman of a seven-party Afghan guerrilla alliance headquartered in <LOCATION> Peshawar </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. He did not elaborate. `` The negotiations and how they will happen will be seen in the future,'' <PERSON> Rabbani </PERSON> told reporters after returning from a five-week trip to northern <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. No comment to the report was immediately available from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. In negotiating a U.N.-mediated agreement in April to withdraw Soviet troops, <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> did not meet with the U.S.-backed guerrillas and spoke instead with Pakistani officials. <PERSON> Rabbani </PERSON> ruled out any coalition government that included communists but he said there was room in a guerrilla-controlled government for `` some elements from <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>.'' `` Non-communist elements working in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> could be included,'' he said. Official Radio <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> on Sunday did not identify the Americans reportedly killed in the attack a day earlier, but a <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> diplomat in <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION> denied <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizens were in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> on government business. The broadcast contended the Americans were helping the guerrillas. The diplomat, speaking on condition of anonymity, said he had heard nothing of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> citizens being killed in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. Soviet officials often have alleged that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> personnel trains guerrilla forces near the Afghan border in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. American reporters often travel to the Afghan capital, <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, and to other areas. Radio <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, in a broadcast monitored in <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION>, said the Americans and two Pakistani officers died Saturday when government forces attacked Moslem guerrilla positions near <LOCATION> Gardez </LOCATION> city, about 60 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Beck </PERSON> said she knew nothing of the report and said she could not even say whether any Americans were in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. In recent years, three Americans have been killed in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> _ <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornton </PERSON>, a reporter for the <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> newspaper, and independent filmmakers <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON> of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bergen </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Landiloff </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. The Pakistani government had no immediate comment on the report. In other developments, the Afghan <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> sent its 100th note of protest alleging Pakistani violations of the U.N.-mediated agreement aimed at ending the fighting in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. The accord, signed April 14 in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, requires the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to withdraw its armed forces from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> by February. The Soviets say half of