<HEAD>Claim Filed Over Yellowstone Fire Damage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man who lost a cabin to this summer's fires in the <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> <LOCATION> National </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> area has filed a claim with the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and expects others to join in his legal action. Dr. <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> Watters </PERSON>, whose $ 60,000, nearly finished cabin in <LOCATION> Cooke </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pass </LOCATION> north of <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> was one of four destroyed when a backfire started by firefighters roared out of control, predicts a rash of lawsuits against the government unless it properly reimburses property owners for their losses. `` There will be the darnedest class-action lawsuit you ever saw in your life,'' he told the <ORGANIZATION> Denver </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>. Fires charred more than 1.6 million acres in the worst fire season in the park's history. `` I think we were betrayed,'' said <PERSON> Charlotte </PERSON> <PERSON> Ficken </PERSON> of <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>, whose mobile home southeast of <LOCATION> Cooke </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mont. </LOCATION>, was destroyed by fires despite firefighters' assurances it would be protected. `` I just do n't think we got any help. So we just burned.'' Federal policies call for claims to be paid only if government negligence can be proven, but <PERSON> Watters </PERSON> said he does not believe that will be a problem. `` The -LRB- National -RRB- <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> realizes they blew it,'' he said. `` They tell you now that they were suppressing those fires, but they were n't. They were as proud as peacocks of those natural fires that they were letting burn _ and then they let things get away from them.'' Under <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> policies, naturally caused fires in parks or wilderness areas were allowed to burn unless they threatened structures or safety. Both agencies switched to the offensive against fires in July because of extremely dry conditions. A number of business owners around the park have claimed they lost money because the fires discouraged travelers from visiting the <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> area. Four <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> counties have been declared disaster areas, clearing the way for low-interest loans, but the loans are not expected to help those who lost summer or permanent homes or outfitters who lost business because of the fires.
