<HEAD>Two Die In Climbing Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANCONIA, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two <ORGANIZATION> Dartmouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> graduate students who were rappelling down steep cliffs were killed after plunging to a trail below, authorities said today. `` They were rappelling down and apparently were both tied to the same anchor point, and when one fell it broke the point where it was tied off,'' said Maj. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Mock </PERSON> of the state Fish and Game Department. About 50 rescuers worked more than five hours on 4,060-foot Cannon Mountain to retrieve the bodies of <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Sunshine </PERSON>, 24, of <LOCATION> Irvine </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Fragge </PERSON>, 23, of <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mitchell </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Mock </PERSON> said. The two were climbing a section of Cannon Cliffs called `` Beware of the Dog.'' Mock said authorities had not determined how far the two fell, but believe the accident happened at 3:38 p.m. Sunday because a watch strapped to one of the climber's packs was smashed and had stopped at that time. Two other climbers who were hiking the trail below Cannon Cliffs found the bodies at 5:20 p.m., <PERSON> Mock </PERSON> said. Both men were engineering students at <ORGANIZATION> Dartmouth </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Thayer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> Dartmouth </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>.
