<HEAD>U.S. Physicians Say Iraq Used Gas Against its Kurdish Population</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to ADD description of weapons, background
on Turkish report, details; PICKS up 3rd graf pvs, `Cook-Deegan
said ...' Minor editing to TRIM.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ZEYNEP ALEMDAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A group of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> physicians that toured Kurdish refugee camps has concluded <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> used chemical weapons against the ethnic Kurdish minority in northern <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, a spokesman said. Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Mullan </PERSON> <PERSON> Cook-Deegan </PERSON>, representing the Boston-based <ORGANIZATION> Physicians </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION>, said <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> most likely used `` a high dose of one of the kind of irritant agents or a nerve agent.'' He did not elaborate. The physician also accused <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> of covering up <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s use of chemical weapons for security and economic reasons. <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> wants to keep good relations with <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and win a role in rebuilding the nation after its 8-year war with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. A Turkish government report maintains no traces of poison gas were found on the refugees during medical screenings. But Turkish officials have said their report does not eliminate the possibility that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> used such weapons. <PERSON> Cook-Deegan </PERSON> said the group's findings were based on interviews with more than 100 Kurds who fled into <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> and also on medical questionnaires given to 25 refugees. The doctor, a senior associate working for the office of Technology Assessment at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, spoke to The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in an interview Thursday on condition the information be used Sunday after the three-member delegation left <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>. The team's other two members were Dr. <PERSON> Howaro </PERSON> <PERSON> Hu </PERSON> from the <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Asfandiar </PERSON> <PERSON> Shukri </PERSON>, a Detroit-based physician. About 60,000 Kurds fled to <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> in August, claiming <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> dropped chemical bombs on their settlements. They now live in five tent cities in southeastern <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>. `` It is difficult to explain the sudden exodus of people that were used to being shot at. If it would have been a conventional weapon attack, there would have been evidence of physical injuries such as bullet wounds,'' <PERSON> Cook-Deegan </PERSON> said. `` <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> used chemical weapons particularly on a population within its border,'' he said. He said the Kurdish refugees most commonly complained about bloody diarrhea, vomiting, skin irritation, and eye and respiratory problems. `` Those are very typical symptoms of chemical agents called irritants,'' <PERSON> Cook-Deegan </PERSON> said. He added that the refugees also described small animals such as birds and bees dying right after the attack. <PERSON> Cook-Deegan </PERSON> criticized the Turkish government for witholding information about the issue. He said the Turkish government also did not release the results of autopsy reports on Kurdish refugees who died immediately after arriving in <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>. The Turkish government announced a month ago that it would turn down any efforts to send <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> experts into <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> to determine if <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> used poison gas against Kurds. The 14-page questionnaire used by the three-member team contained dozens of queries requiring detailed answers about the respondent's health before and after the attack. <PERSON> Cook-Deegan </PERSON> said they will analyze the questionnaires and prepare a report in a month. Investigators for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> also reported after touring the refugee camps in <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> used chemical weapons in attacks to depopulate <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s Kurdish regions. `` We find no question that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s policy in <LOCATION> Kurdistan </LOCATION> has the characteristics of genocide,'' the two staff members, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Galbraith </PERSON> and <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Von </PERSON> <PERSON> Hollen </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, concluded in a report to the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commitee </ORGANIZATION> chairman, <PERSON> Claiborne </PERSON> <PERSON> Pell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-R.I. </LOCATION>, last month. The Kurds, 20 million people living in a region that lies in <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, have been fighting battles for independence for the past century. The latest rebellion took advantage of <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s war with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. Soon after an Aug. 20 cease-fire went into effect in that war, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> turned upon the Kurds, unleashing war-hardened elite troops upon the Kurdish guerrillas.
