<HEAD>Bush Resumes Attack on Dukakis on Defense</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 10 grafs new with speech today; pick up 6th graf pvs bgng
``Bush enjoyed...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> today resumed his attack on presidential rival <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> as weak on defense, accusing the Democrat of spreading `` misinformation'' about the state of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military forces. The Republican vice president, in remarks prepared for delivery at a <ORGANIZATION> Martin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marietta </ORGANIZATION> defense contractor plant, said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is `` trying desperately to jump into the mainstream'' by acknowledging a need to modernize land-based defenses. `` But there is strong reason to doubt that he would do it, especially when it comes to modernizing our land-based missiles. He still opposes the MX and he thinks the Midgetman costs too much. So he says he's going to work with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to find another way. `` Wake up, governor, we've done all that,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, adding that in 1983 the bipartisan <ORGANIZATION> Scowcroft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> was formed to study national defense issues. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> called on <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> to stop spreading what he called `` misinformation'' about the state of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces. `` It's not 1980 anymore. Our divisional war fighting capabilities have improved by an average of 60 percent since 1980,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` Notwithstanding my opponents' claims, only a few of the A-6's are grounded because of wing cracks _ not one third. We've got the money to fix them as fast as the manufacturer can do it. `` Governor, it's time to stop running down our defenses,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. In his first news conference in more than two weeks, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said Sunday that questions such as a query about his agenda for the first 60 days in office `` are putting me beyond where I want to be.'' `` So if I do n't answer some of them from here on in it is because I'm focusing on November 8 and I do n't want to be dragged beyond that because things seem to be going well now,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> nominee has a solid lead in many national polls and <ORGANIZATION> Electoral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> surveys. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> enjoyed a low-key Sunday, joining family members at a football game between the <ORGANIZATION> Denver </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broncos </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Atlanta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Falcons </ORGANIZATION>. The vice president, who viewed the game from a private box, was introduced at halftime to a mixture of cheers and boos. At the news conference, the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> nominee declined to say what budget cuts he would make to balance the budget, and was unspecific when asked how he would deal with funding for the Nicaraguan rebels and whether the homeless problem warrants special Cabinet-level supervision. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he already has a team studying the transition to a <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> presidency and that he is ready to name his Cabinet quickly. Former <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> Undersecretary <PERSON> Chase </PERSON> <PERSON> Untermeyer </PERSON> heads the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> transition team. `` He has drawn up wiring diagrams, what we should do if we win,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` You have to hit the ground running.'' The vice president, however, scoffed at suggestions that he already had decided on most of the <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> members he would choose. `` I ca n't let myself think about that. ... I'm not going to do something that dumb and shift gears,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. Referring to his escalating poll ratings since Thursday's debate, he said, `` I can tell you I've been encouraged _ certainly not one scintilla of overconfidence. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> did not disclose where he would make deficit-reducing budget cuts, because that is something he will work out with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> when the times comes, according to his staff. `` You have to sit down and know the facts at the time,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said at the news conference. On how he would handle the Contra situation in light of the rebels' diminished military capacity, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, `` I ca n't give you what I'll do after I become president, but I'm a strong believer that we made a big mistake, the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> did, in not supporting the resistance ... I would simply take a hard look when I got there, see what the facts were at the time, and try to help the forces that want democracy.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he would put his vice president in charge of a national anti-drug program, but when asked what other duties he would give him, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said only that it would be `` a wide area of assignments based on the model of the last two administrations.'' As to whether the homeless problem might merit special oversight by the vice president, he replied: `` There's a lot of problems of sufficient severity to require the attention of the president and vice president. Whether that means setting up some special operation, I could n't possibly say.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> maintained that he can balance the budget by 1992 under his `` flexible freeze'' plan to limit federal spenfing to the rate of inflation, with cuts off-setting each new spending item. He has listed some areas where he would spend more money, including education, child care and cleaning up the environment, but has refused to list cuts. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> conceded that, for his idea to work, interest rates would have to decline by several percentage points from current levels.
