bgng, While the.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EUCLID, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Underdog <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, trying to reverse his slide in pre-election polls, declared in the industrial Middle West today that Republican rival <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` sat on his hands while <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s industrial heartland has been fighting for its life.'' In a speech at the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brass </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Copper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the Democratic presidential nominee said that `` here in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> you've lost thousands of manufacturing jobs And just last week we learned that we had more imports coming into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in August than in any month in history.'' Aides said that in the final three weeks of the campaign, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> would sharpen the differences between him and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, particularly on economic issues. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> arrived in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> shortly after publication of a new poll by the <ORGANIZATION> Akron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beacon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> which showed him trailing <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in this critical state by 11 points. Political aide <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> dismissed the poll, saying the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> electorate is `` volatile.'' <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, he said, `` is winnable.'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was spending a full day in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> to be followed by a similar all-day foray into <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>. `` The sense is that you want to create a bigger impact on a state by putting a lot of attention on it in one day,'' he said. Asked in which major states <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is now trailing, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> would only reply, `` They're all competitive.'' In his Euclid speech, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said that while <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> talks about `` a kinder, gentler nation,'' his record contradicts that message. `` His record tells the people of <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, ` We do n't care enough about you to protect you from the nuclear weapons facilities that are poisoning your water and threatening the safety of your workers','' he said. `` And I ` m here to tell you that in a Dukakis-Bentsen administration, we'll have an Energy Department that makes sure that its citizens and communities are never again threatened by nuclear waste and deadly radioactive clouds,'' he said. On foreign trade, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` has not given the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people a clue as to what he would do. Mr. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s trade policy is like a rerun of ` Let's Make a Deal,' letting the voters guess what's behind door No. 1, door No. 2 and door No. 3.'' The <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor said he would `` open the doors of foreign markets to <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> products, because I want an <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> more concerned with selling American goods abroad than selling American debt abroad.'' At a hometown rally in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> on Sunday, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> cast the Nov. 8 election as a contest between his middle-class work ethic and penthouse Republicans who support <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. `` I enter the last three weeks of this campaign as an underdog, fighting for the values I believe in,'' he said. While the emphasis in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> was on values, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> aide <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Dach </PERSON> said the Democratic nominee would concentrate on spelling out `` two different visions of our economic future'' during appearances in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> over the next three days. `` The close of the campaign is going to be headed by a focus on the economic issues,'' said <PERSON> Dach </PERSON>. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> told supporters in historic <LOCATION> Faneuil </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hall </LOCATION>, where leaders of the American Revolution often met, that Republicans were `` already celebrating; they're popping champagne corks in their penthouses. But I've got news for those Republicans; we're going to be the ones celebrating on election night.'' Emphasizing the differences between himself and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, the Democratic nominee said, `` I believe in an <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> that's in command of its destiny and takes charge of its future.'' He said the vice president `` sat on the sidelines for eight years while <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> got beaten in world markets, while they mortgaged our children's future to a mountain of debt, and a piece of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> was being sold off every day at bargain basement prices.'' Said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>: `` I believe <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s leaders must strive to do the right thing; but we must admit it _ and correct it _ when we do the wrong thing. ... I've taken responsibility for my mistakes. But Mr. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> takes responsibility for nothing.'' `` I believe in the value of work,'' said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, while <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` saw nothing, said nothing and did nothing while his <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> colleagues in the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> used every trick in the book to keep the minimum wage a poverty wage.'' `` Ask Mr. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>,'' he went on `` if he can look a woman in the eye who scrubs floors for a living to support her family on $ 3.35 an hour.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign manager <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Estrich </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dach </PERSON> denied the accuracy of a <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> story on Sunday that said he would concentrate his efforts on 18 states and the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> with 272 electoral votes _ two more than needed for election. The list contained most of the major states _ <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> _ that both sides describe as key battlegrounds. Also on the list were <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>. Given lower priority, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, were <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, home state of <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> vice presidential nominee <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>. `` It is not -LRB- accurate -RRB-,'' said <PERSON> Estrich </PERSON>. `` We are not writing off whole regions of the country,'' she said. She noted that while the story put <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> among the states being given less priority, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> would be in both this week.
