<SECOND>AM-Hirohito,0167</SECOND>
<HEAD>Emperor in Serious But Stable Condition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> remained in serious but stable condition Monday, nearly one month after suffering internal bleeding, palace officials said. <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>, 87, fell ill Sept. 19, and has been bedridden since. `` The emperor as usual is fully conscious,'' said <PERSON> Kenji </PERSON> <PERSON> Maeda </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Imperial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Household </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. Doctors gave <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> nearly a half-pint of blood Monday. Since Sept. 19, he has received more than 18 pints to replace the blood lost and to combat anemia. The Imperial Household Agency has released little information about the nature of his illness beyond releasing his temperature and pulse and respiration rates three times daily and the amount of blood <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> has received. News reports have said the emperor has pancreatic cancer. The agency has neither confirmed nor denied the reports and has urged the media to refrain from such speculation. <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> has no political power but serves as a symbol of national unity.
</TEXT>
