<TEXT>
 Here is a sampling of what media around the world are saying about the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> presidential election:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>JAPAN</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The liberal-leaning <ORGANIZATION> Asahi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shimbun </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> said Monday that Thursday's debate between Republican Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Democratic Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> `` lacked meat.'' `` <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> merely reiterated that he would not raise taxes and indicated no convincing measure for reducing <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s ` twin deficits' that have been affecting not only the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy but the global economy as well. And <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> ... failed to explain how he intended to fund his ambitious welfare policy. `` We found it most unfortunate that what we consider a ` mud-slinging contest' _ believed to have been started by the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> camp _ escalated in this debate and consequently blurred more important policy issues. And <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, who is said to be faltering, apparently tried to recover his ground by pushing harsher measures against <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trading partners and foreign investors as a means for winning voter approval. We were alarmed and disturbed by this.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ITALY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Vittorio </PERSON> <PERSON> Zucconi </PERSON>, reporting from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for the liberal Rome-based newspaper <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Repubblica </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s largest-selling national, said the debate virtually ended the contest. `` <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s designated heir checked the weary punches thrown by the Greek from <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> in the previous direct meeting, and now the people murmur ` It's over, it's done,''' he wrote.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Ennio </PERSON> <PERSON> Caretto </PERSON>, reporting from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for the moderate Turin-based newspaper <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stampa </ORGANIZATION>, wrote on Friday: `` Never like yesterday have the Democrats felt they lacked a charismatic leader who knows how to show the country the gravity of its problems and the unknown factor of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> inheritance, to make it recapture the taste of combat and change.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Siegmund </PERSON> <PERSON> Ginzberg </PERSON>, reporting from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> for the Rome-based <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> newspaper <ORGANIZATION> l'Unita </ORGANIZATION>, wrote that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> won the debate `` not with a TKO but with boring technique.'' `` <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, magisterially prepared by his directors, turned out to be, even in presenting himself with an unchanging ` manly look,' capable of touching the sentimental feelings of the public. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> instead turned out to appear like an iceberg, detached and identifying himself with the image of a ` computer without a heart.'''
