he Potwisha Camp Ground about 30 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Visalia </LOCATION> and 175 miles north of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. The fire was blamed on a careless camper, Ms. <PERSON> Case </PERSON> said. An 800-acre brush fire in <LOCATION> Riverside </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Hemet </LOCATION> burned out of control about 85 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, but firefighters were gaining the upper hand and predicted control later today, said <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forestry </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Joanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>. Two smaller fires erupted in the mountainous eastern portion of the Angeles National Forest. One, a 55-acre blaze started by children playing with matches and a cigarette lighter, destroyed a house before it was extinguished. Firefighters were keeping the other one, a 150-acre fire, from crossing a ridge this morning but had not contained it, authorities said.
