<HEAD>Former Reagan Aide Linda Chavez Quits U.S. English Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former White House aide <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON> said today she is quitting as president of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> English after being told that at least one major contributor to the group has advocated forced sterilization. `` I am resigning,'' she said. `` To me, it is just not consistent with the views I hold.'' Veteran CBS newsman <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Cronkite </PERSON> resigned from the group's advisory board last week after being told of a 1986 memo by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> English Chairman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tanton </PERSON> that raised the spectre of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> becoming overwhelmed by foreign-speaking have-nots Ms. <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> candidate for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> from <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> in 1986 and a former aide in the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> last week that she might follow suit if <PERSON> Tanton </PERSON> did not step down following a weekend board meeting. On Monday, she said she had since learned that at least one major contributor had helped reprint `` an awful, awful book'' called `` Coup of the Saints'' which she described as `` a paranoid fantasy'' about `` undesirables of the Third World'' taking over developed nations. At least one major contributor has given money to `` groups that may be involved in eugenics research,'' she added. Ms. <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON> did not identify the contributor or contributors about whom she was speaking but said she asked <PERSON> Tanton </PERSON> whether he knew of the contributors' other activities. He told her he was n't aware of them A proposition bankrolled by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> English that is on the <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> ballot next month would change the Arizona Constitution to designate English as the state's official language and limit government use of foreign languages in courts, meetings and schools. Similar measures are on the ballot in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON> said she had planned to leave the group anyway following the weekend board meeting but decided after hearing about the contributors that `` I do n't feel that I wish to wait until other details are worked out.'' At their meeting in <LOCATION> Alexandria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> English board of directors decided to review <PERSON> Tanton </PERSON>'s activities in immigration-reform and population-control groups and his 1986 memo before taking any action. <PERSON> Tanton </PERSON> did not immediately return a call seeking comment, and an operator at <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> English in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> said no one else was available. Ms. <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON> said she had sought assurances about the type of backers the organization had before she joined it and had given up administrative control of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> English several weeks ago because the organization's financial records were n't being kept in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` I feel that there were some misrepresentations made,'' she said in a telephone interview from her home in <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION>, a spokesman for opponents of the ballot proposition said word of her resignation would help his efforts. `` This resignation confirms what we have been saying,'' said spokesman <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>. `` It is hard for anyone to support <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tanton </PERSON> and Proposition 106 when the facts are known. One shadowy figure from <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> is pushing his grisly vision upon t