<HEAD>Boy Scouts Told To Yell And Tell When Threatened With Abuse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Boy Scout leaders seeking to ward off child molesters are telling their troops in a `` yell and tell'' campaign that it's okay for a Scout to be rude and even to holler `` no'' if someone tries to do something wrong. The assertiveness training is part of a nationwide Youth Protection Training program unveiled this year by the Boy Scouts of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. `` We know that perverted individuals seek out youth organizations such as Scouts, choirs and teams. What we have done is sharpen our scrutiny and make the Boy Scouts of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> very uncomfortable for pedophiles,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Kephart </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> area scouting director. In his eight years as executive director of <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> scouting headquarters, <PERSON> Kephart </PERSON> said he had heard only four official complaints of molestation. In 24 years of scouting work before that he recalls only one complaint, he said. But <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Accus </PERSON>, spokesman for the Boy Scouts national headquarters in <LOCATION> Irving </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, said at least 100 official accusations of sexual assault have been registered in the past decade nationwide. The program has 1.5 million leaders operating each year. In the past year, Explorer Scout posts in the <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> area have been involved in two sexual assault cases. A former <LOCATION> Douglas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> sheriff's deputy was sentenced in May to nine years in prison for sexual assault on a minor. Three Scouts testified he used his position to gain their trust and manipulated their loyalty to seduce them. Last month a former Explorer Scout accused a <LOCATION> Cherry </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Village </LOCATION> patrolman of sexually abusing her in 1984. The case has not yet come to trial. <PERSON> Kephart </PERSON> has scheduled a Youth Protection workshop Oct. 22 for leaders of nearly 150 metro-area Explorer Scout Posts. Effective last month, anyone wanting to become a Boy Scout leader must submit an application that lists any drug, child abuse or other felony charges. Scouting adminstrators also are teaching leaders to avoid being accused, <PERSON> Kephart </PERSON> said. `` At one time, Scout leaders counseling a kid could shut the door and sit down to talk with him. But now we tell them not to get alone with Scouts,'' <PERSON> Kephart </PERSON> said. In addition to the ban on one-on-one contact, new rules require that at least two supervising adults accompany outings such as campouts. `` It is a great dilemma,'' <PERSON> Kephart </PERSON> said. `` There are plenty of kids out there who really need an arm around their shoulder and some affection. I do n't really think that hugging is completely out. `` But if I want to put an arm around a Scout who has done well, I do it in public and standing in the middle of the room.''
