<HEAD>Simple Funeral for Egypt's Former Queen</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS name of newspaper in 9th graf ``Women in Egypt...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MAURICE GUINDI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Safinaz </PERSON> <PERSON> Zulficar </PERSON>, who reigned as Queen <PERSON> Farida </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> for 11 years before being divorced by her husband <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Farouk </PERSON>, was buried today after a simple funeral. <PERSON> Farida </PERSON>, 67, died on Sunday, almost two weeks after being admitted to a hospital for pneumonia. She spent four days in a coma before her death. President <PERSON> Hosni </PERSON> <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON> assigned his first chamberlain to join about 700 mourners at the funeral. Although it was not a state affair, several senior government officials walked at the head of the procession. The funeral was a far cry from <PERSON> Farouk </PERSON>'s nighttime burial in <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION>, without a procession and with only a few of his closest family members allowed to attend. <PERSON> Farouk </PERSON>, overthrown by the army in 1952 and sent into exile in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, died in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> on March 18, 1965. At the family's request, his body was brought to <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> 12 days later and was buried at <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Al-Rifai </PERSON> Mosque next to his father, King <PERSON> Fuad </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Farida </PERSON>, Arabic for unique, was the name <PERSON> Farouk </PERSON> decided to give his bride after their marriage in 1938, two years after he became king He was 18 then, she 17. They had three daughters, <PERSON> Feria </PERSON>, <PERSON> Fawzia </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fadia </PERSON>. What seemingly began as a happy marriage began to crack up after <PERSON> Farouk </PERSON> started public affairs with other women and frequented night clubs and gambling casinos in the mid-1940s. His popularity dropped as scandal involving him became common knowledge. At the same time, <PERSON> Farida </PERSON>, widely regarded as the wronged partner, gained in public stature. Women in <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> could not sue for divorce at the time, but <PERSON> Farida </PERSON> demanded a divorce, and continued in her efforts despite pressure from government officials to dissuade her, said <ORGANIZATION> Al-Akhbar </ORGANIZATION> newspaper columnist <PERSON> Mustafa </PERSON> <PERSON> Amin </PERSON>, who was close to the royal family. In 1948, <PERSON> Farouk </PERSON> granted the divorce. No reason was given, and other reports said the divorce was caused because <PERSON> Farida </PERSON> did not bear him a son. The ex-queen moved with the daughters to <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> and later moved to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, where she took up painting. <PERSON> Farida </PERSON> returned home in 1982 and settled in a small apartment in <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION>. She held several exhibitions of her paintings, which were mainly depictions of life in <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Al-Ahram </ORGANIZATION> reported today that <PERSON> Farida </PERSON>'s last wish was to see her daughters. All three were summoned from <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, where they live, and were at their mother's bedside when she died. <PERSON> Farida </PERSON> never spoke ill of <PERSON> Farouk </PERSON> in public, despite the anguish she reportedly endured. In a eulogy published today, <PERSON> Amin </PERSON> wrote that she once told him: `` Remember, he was the father of my daughters. Any bad word I utter about him would hurt them.''
