<FIRST>r p AM-PledgeHistory     10-17 0772</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pledge History,760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Socialist Wrote Pledge of Allegiance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Scholars say few people would have been more surprised by the Pledge of Allegiance's prominence in the 1988 presidential campaign than the man who wrote it. He was a socialist. The pledge first appeared in a <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> magazine </ORGANIZATION>, The Youth's Companion, 96 years ago, on Sept. 8, 1892 Although there are competing claims to authorship, most authorities credit the Rev. <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> Bellamy </PERSON>, a Baptist minister who preached against big business and served as vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialists </ORGANIZATION>. His daughter-in-law, <PERSON> Rachel </PERSON> <PERSON> Bellamy </PERSON>, 92, of <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, recalls him as tall, proud and `` kind of stuffy.'' She said he eventually left the ministry because he felt the church `` was not doing enough to help the working man.'' <PERSON> Louise </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Providence </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> R.I. </LOCATION>, who has written two books on the history of the pledge, believes <PERSON> Bellamy </PERSON>'s congregation grew tired of his political homilies _ one was entitled `` Jesus the Socialist'' _ and forced him out of the pulpit. In any event, <PERSON> Bellamy </PERSON> joined the staff of The Youth's Companion in 1891 and apparently composed the pledge a few months later, while the magazine was in the midst of a campaign to sell <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> flags. The Youth's Companion had pioneered the sale of subscription `` premiums'' ranging from school uniforms to silver tea services. But it achieved its greatest commercial success, and its enduring legacy, with its drive to put a flag in every school in the land. The flags were priced at $ 3.30 to $ 13, depending on size. To help schools raise the money, the magazine provided `` flag certificates'' that pupils could sell for 10 cents apiece. Starting a year early, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Youth </ORGANIZATION>'s Companion urged school children to prepare to celebrate the 400th anniversary of <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>' voyage to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, which was coming up in October 1892 To show it was truly companionable, the magazine even published a suggested `` Columbian Celebration'' ceremony. Most of it just happened to require a flag. Sandwiched between a presidential proclamation and an ode to <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>, both long forgotten, was the original 23-word pledge, memorable both for its sentiment and its economy of phrasing: `` I pledge allegiance to my flag and to the republic for which it stands: one nation, indivisible, with liberty and justice for all.'' It was not until 1923 that the words `` my flag'' were replaced by `` the flag of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'' out of concern that immigrant children might otherwise think they were pledging allegiance to some other flag. The phrase `` under God'' was inserted in 1954 at the behest of President <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON>, who said that `` in this way we shall constantly strengthen those spiritual weapons which forever will be our country's most powerful resource in peace and war.'' The original version of the pledge was not signed, but once it had caught on in the schools, rival claims to authorship quickly emerged. One group pushed for <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Upham </PERSON>, an editor of The Youth's Companion. The other favored <PERSON> Bellamy </PERSON>. <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> and a few other scholars argue that <PERSON> Upham </PERSON> was the author. But two formal investigations, one conducted by the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Flag Association in 1939 and the other by the Library of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1957, concluded that <PERSON> Bellamy </PERSON> was responsible. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitman </PERSON>, a researcher in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, says <PERSON> Bellamy </PERSON> espoused `` a relatively benign form'' of socialism. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION>, which he belonged to, wanted to nationalize chunks of the American economy but have them controlled at the municipal level. ... He did not practice or preach violent overthrow of the government by any means,'' <PERSON> Whitman </PERSON> said. Controversy over the pledge erupted in the 1940s, when <PERSON> Jehovah </PERSON>'s Witnesses refused to recite it in the public schools Members of the sect said swearing allegiance to a material object violated their religious principles, which dictated allegiance only to God. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> initially rejected such arguments, ruling in a 1940 case that public schools could expel children who did not recite the pledge. The court reversed itself in 1943 and said children could not be compelled to recite the pledge. Meantime, <PERSON> Jehovah </PERSON>'s Witnesses had been subjected to vicious attacks in dozens of communities. In <LOCATION> Richwood </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, for example, members of the sheriff's department and <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legion </ORGANIZATION> forced seven members of the sect to drink large quantities of castor oil, then tied them together and paraded them through the town. `` <PERSON> Bellamy </PERSON> was an avid fan of saying the pledge,'' said <PERSON> Whitman </PERSON>, `` but I ca n't imagine how he would have felt about it if he had lived to see the mob violence of the 40s.''
</TEXT>
