<HEAD>Business Inventories Continue to Rise, But Sales Outstrip Them</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Business inventories continued their steady rise in August, the government said Monday, but economists remain untroubled because the expansion is not outpacing strong sales. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said goods held on shelves and backlots rose 0.8 percent to $ 733.7 billion, following a 0.7 percent gain in July. It was the 20th consecutive monthly increase. Rising inventories can be a sign of economic sluggishness as manufacturers order production cuts and layoffs while goods in reserve are sold off. However, analysts are not particularly troubled by current inventory levels because sales also have been strong. Compared with a year ago, inventories are up 8.7 percent while sales are up 8.0 percent. The department said August sales totaled $ 487.7 billion, up a brisk 1.1 percent from July, when the gain was a slight 0.1 percent. It was the ninth increase in a row. `` If we're looking for a reason for a slowdown in 1989, it wo n't be excess inventory building ... Typically recessions develop when there are excess levels of inventory and we're not looking at those levels this year,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hagens </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wefa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, a <PERSON> Bala </PERSON> <PERSON> Cynwyd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, forecasting firm. Inventory accumulation in August was led by a 1.4 percent rise at retailers, where sales are the slowest. Wholesale inventories were up 0.6 percent while inventories at factories, where an export boom has kept sales strongest, increased 0.5 percent. However, half of the inventory buildup among retailers is accounted for by a 2.9 percent rise at auto dealers. Car sales have been strong this year, so dealers did not offer price cuts or financing incentives to move cars from the old model year off their lots. `` Inventories are in pretty good shape, with the notable exception of apparel,'' said <PERSON> Maury </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` However, the overall inventory level wo n't remain in good shape unless retail sales pick up in October and November But I think they will.'' In sales, a 2.1 percent increase at manufacturing plants more than offset a 0.1 percent decline at the retail level. Wholesalers reported a 0.7 percent increase. An advance estimate of retail sales for September, released last week, showed a 0.4 percent decline. The combination of moderately strong gain in inventories and an even more robust sales increase left the inventory-to-sales ratio at 1.50, unchanged from July and June and up slightly from 1.49 a year ago. That means it would take 1.5 months to exhaust inventories at the August sales pace, a ratio not considered unusually high.
