<HEAD>Rocket Test Firing Scheduled Wednesday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A space shuttle main rocket engine will be test-fired Wednesday at the <ORGANIZATION> Marshall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, the first extended firing since the roar of Saturn rockets echoed across <LOCATION> Huntsville </LOCATION> in the 1960s. `` It's going to be something <LOCATION> Huntsville </LOCATION> has n't heard for quite awhile,'' <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Dom </PERSON> <PERSON> Amatore </PERSON> said. The 15-second firing is part of a series of tests on the shuttle main engines and coincides with the city's `` Space Awareness Week.'' <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> engineers want to determine how long the rocket motors, fueled by hydrogen and oxygen from the shuttle's huge external tank, can run if needed. The engines now operate for about eight minutes during a shuttle launch. Shuttle engine No. 0208, installed in the test stand in August, was `` warmed up'' in a 1.5-second start test last month. After this week's test, a third test firing of 45 seconds will be scheduled in November. <PERSON> Amatore </PERSON> said the primary goal of the first brief tests is to verify that <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> can handle the firings and whether a metal `` flame bucket'' on the test stand can handle the rocket exhaust. The last test firing of a big rocket motor at <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> was a Saturn test on Sept. 11, 1969, about two months after men first set foot on the moon. <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> is <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s main propulsion center. In addition to developing the Saturn rockets, it manages space shuttle propulsion systems, including the main engines and solid fuel booster rockets, which are test-fired in <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>. `` Space Awareness Week'' includes a visit by the crew of the shuttle Discovery. The five astronaunts who flew last month in the first post-Challenger shuttle mission are to be in <LOCATION> Huntsville </LOCATION> on Thursday and Friday to thank <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> engineers. They also will lead a parade and appear at a public reception Thursday. On Wednesday, singer <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Denver </PERSON> and former <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> senator and Apollo astronaut <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> <PERSON> Schmitt </PERSON> will be in town to discuss proposed new space missions. <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>, who hopes to ride into orbit with a Soviet crew in 1990, will talk about <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> observation missions while <PERSON> Schmitt </PERSON> will discuss proposals for manned missions to the <LOCATION> moon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mars </LOCATION>.
