<HEAD>5th Circuit: U.S. Companies Overseas Don't Have To Meet Civil
Rights Laws</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies operating abroad do not have to comply with the civil rights law forbidding discrimination on the job, a federal appeals court ruled Monday. The 2-1 ruling by the 5th <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> upheld a lower court ruling against <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Boureslan </PERSON>, a naturalized <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizen who was born in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> and employed by <ORGANIZATION> Aramco </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Dhahran </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>. He filed suit under Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964, contending that he was fired in June 1984 after a harassment campaign by his supervisor _ `` a campaign which took the form of racial, religious and ethnic slurs,'' the 5th Circuit said. The seven-page majority ruling by Judge <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> said the court could not find any indication in the law or in its legislative history that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> had meant to extend civil rights protection to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizens employed abroad. Arguments that it is unfair to deny Americans employed abroad protections to which they are entitled in this country are appealing, but do not overcome other strong policy arguments, <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> wrote. `` The religious and social customs practiced in many countries are wholly at odds with those of this country,'' the ruling said. `` Requiring American employers to comply with Title VII in such a country could well leave <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> corporations the difficult choice of either refusing to employ <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in the country or discontinuing business.'' In a strong 17-page dissent, Judge <PERSON> Carolyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Dineen </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> said it may be necessary to enforce the law abroad to be sure that minorities and women have an equal chance at home. `` Today's decision means that one <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizen assigned to the Saudi office of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corporation, and another <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizen working for the same company in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> could experience identical acts of discrimination, but only the latter will have a remedy. This situation creates a dilemma for minorities and women: foreign assignments will be less attractive, while refusal of such an assignment could limit an individual's opportunity for advancement,'' she wrote. She noted that assignement to a foreign office is frequently a required step for promotion within a multinational corporation. This means, she said, that this country may have to enforce its civil rights laws abroad to ensure equal chances at foreign assignments that would affect employment opportunities in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Her dissent agreed with other arguments brought up by <PERSON> Boureslan </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> Equal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opportunities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, which entered a friend-of-the-court brief. They argued that a section exempting aliens working for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corporations in other countries showed that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> did intend it to apply to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizens under such circumstances.
