adds three grafs on end with detail from indictment.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DICK PETTYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rep. <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> was indicted today on charges of perjury, accused of lying to a federal grand jury investigating money laundering. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Barr </PERSON> said <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON>, a Republican, was indicted on 10 counts of perjury over his testimony before a grand jury last February about a sting in which a federal agent posed as a money launderer. <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON>'s office said today he had no immediate response to the announcement. But he had said Sunday, during a television interview, that he expected to be indicted and was glad because he hoped it would give him a chance to clear his name before his re-election bid goes to the voters Nov. 8. In an unusually bitter race, <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON>, 47, is seeking a third term from suburban <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>'s 4th District against <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> opponent <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, 46, a former actor on television's `` Dukes of Hazzard'' who lost to <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> in 1986. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> has criticized <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> ever since the money-laundering-related charges were first aired, while <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> has assailed <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>' past conviction on a charge of wife-beating, a conviction <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> says stemmed from alcohol abuse that he has since overcome. In Sunday's interview, <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> said he expected to be arraigned this afternoon and planned to waive a number of rights, including the right to charge the government with misconduct in the case, so that he can go on trial next Monday. <PERSON> Barr </PERSON> said he did not know whether such a quick trial would be possible. <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> said he planned to represent himself at the trial. `` I am actually excited because it will be the first opportunity I am going to have to clear the air, clear my name and give the voters a legitimate race based on the issues,'' <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> said in the interview Sunday. Angered by continued reports linking his name with the grand jury investigation, <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> took the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor on Oct. 3 to demand an immediate indictment. <PERSON> Barr </PERSON> said the timing of the indictment `` has nothing whatsoever to do with politics'' or <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON>'s request to be indicted. <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> was first linked publicly to the money laundering investigation earlier this year when it was disclosed that his Aug. 28, 1987, meeting with an undercover federal agent posing as a money launderer for underworld figures had been videotaped. `` Money laundering'' is a term for various methods of getting around federal currency laws by transferring illicitly raised cash _ drug money, for example _ into bank accounts in such a way that its origin is hid. <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> was introduced to the undercover agent by <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> LeChasney </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> businessman who was active in Republican circles. LeChasney is one of the two men scheduled to go on trial next week on money-laundering charges. <PERSON> LeChasney </PERSON> and several <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> aides testified before the grand jury last month. <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> testified before the grand jury in February. In June, <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> newspapers obtained several tape recordings from the investigation and published excerpts from a series of conversations between <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON>, <PERSON> LeChasney </PERSON> and the undercover agent. The tapes showed that <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> continued to pursue negotiations for an $ 850,000 home construction loan after being told it might be financed with drug money he would be helping to launder. <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> was quoted on the tapes as saying that the source of the money was `` <PERSON> Charles </PERSON>' problem,'' since LeChasney would be obtaining the money to lend to <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON>. He added, `` I frankly do n't think it's incumbent upon me to go out and find out where <ORGANIZATION> XYZ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> gets their money, or, for that matter, where <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> gets their money. If they set back the odometer, that's their problem.'' He ended the negotiations after being told he would have to accept the money in person in cash and sign a receipt. <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> later apologized for his role in the negotiations, calling it a mistake in judgment, but he denied any wrongdoing. He also asked the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> ethics committee to determine if he had violated any law or House rule. The panel agreed to investigate, but has not issued a ruling. The indictment said <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> lied when he told the grand jury last February that he did not have any concrete indication that <PERSON> LeChasney </PERSON> and the undercover agent were discussing illegal activities. <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> testified that he was suspicious of the agent, but did not have enough information to report the matter to authorities, the indictment said. Another count of the indictment accuses <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> of lying when he denied the agent discussed keeping the large cash loan from being reported to federal regulators.
