and groups associated with him. It added that he has not filed a federal income tax return since at least 1979. `` This is a screwball charge,'' <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON> said. `` The government does not charge I evaded taxes, because I have made clear I have no money income.'' He said he relied on the gifts of friends and being `` hosted'' by various organizations and conferences. `` There is no tax liability.'' <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON> added, `` I had nothing to do with raising $ 34 million.'' He said he had counseled some groups but never had authority over them and that the central organization described in the indictment does not exist. `` This is a malicious, vindictive prosecution,'' he said. <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON>, who is campaigning in 12 states and the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, said he believed that Democratic presidential nominee <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> prevailed on like-minded federal prosecutors in the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration to seek the indictment, because <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON> has predicted dire consequences if <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is elected. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hudson </PERSON> said last Friday that <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON> was being treated like any other citizen accused of a crime. The seven defendants were all released on their own personal recognizance but pledged to pay $ 5,000 if they fail to appear for court dates. Judge <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> allowed them unlimited travel in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and abroad so long as they informed the court clerk in advance. Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Kent </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> had objected to international travel but was overruled. <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> made clear he plans to move the case quickly, saying `` 90 percent of the -LRB-