<FIRST>r w AM-ChildHunger     10-17 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Child Hunger,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey Suggests Millions of U.S. Children May Suffer Hunger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A house-to-house survey of nearly 800 low-income families in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state suggests that as many as 5 million of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s children suffer from hunger, a private activist group said Monday. The <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> And </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> is extending the study to seven other states over the next 15 months. But on the basis of the early data from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state `` ... we estimate conservatively that 2 million to 5 million children in this country could now have a serious hunger problem,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fersh </PERSON>, executive director of the center. `` We believe that this estimate is conservative because it attempts only to estimate the number of children living in poverty who might be hungry,'' said <PERSON> Fersh </PERSON>. `` It does not include any children from families with incomes above the poverty line who might be hungry.'' At the same time, <PERSON> Fersh </PERSON> acknowledged that he has no way of knowing whether the survey results in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state will be replicated in larger studies. Similar studies are now under way in <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The survey techiques were first used in a 1986 survey in <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> and refined for the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state and ongoing studies, all of which involve selecting low-income families at random and then conducting face-to-face interviews that take about 45 minutes each. The responses given by mothers to a lengthy questionnaire are correlated with other information such as family income and what, if any, public assistance such as food stamps they receive. Among the questions: Does your household ever run out of money to buy food to make a meal? Do your children ever eat less than you feel they should because there is not enough money for food? A respondent had to answer `` yes'' to at least five such questions before being placed in the hunger category. Dr. <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Sidel </PERSON>, a professor of social medicine at the <ORGANIZATION> Albert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Einstein </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, headed the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>'s technical advisory committee and said the survey techniques used are the best yet developed for measuring hunger. `` The evidence is in. The evidence is clear. The evidence is scientific,'' he said. <PERSON> Sidel </PERSON> emphasized that the kind of hunger seen among <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s children is not of the dramatic, life-threatening variety common in <LOCATION> African </LOCATION> countries But he said there are `` other kinds of medical and physical consequences'' inexcusable in a country as rich as the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` It is a violation of equality of opportunity to force -LRB- poor -RRB- children to go to school hungry,'' said <PERSON> Sidel </PERSON>. <PERSON> Fersh </PERSON> said one major finding of the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state study is that it shows `` people do not supplement to the extent the food stamp program assumes'' the amount of assistance they get from that particular <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> program. The reason, he said, is that they are paying ever higher prices for rent, child care and medical costs. `` The food budget is the most elastic,'' he said, and that is what is cut first. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state was not singled out because hunger was believed better or worse, but as an outgrowth of the Governor's Task Force on Hunger created there in 1986 to try to document the extent and nature of hunger in the state. The <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> relies on the support of foundations, religious groups, corporations, individuals and others to carry out its hunger and poverty programs.
