<FIRST>r a AM-CDC--RadiationStudy     10-17 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CDC--Radiation Study,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>CDC To Study Possible Victims Of Radioactive Spills At Hanford</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Government researchers are investigating whether as many as 20,000 people who lived near the <LOCATION> Hanford </LOCATION> nuclear reservation in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state in the 1940s and early 1950s were contaminated by radioactive spills. The federal <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> said the leakage over about nine years of several radioactive elements, especially Iodine 131, apparently is the most massive radioactive leak of any facility in the country. The reservation opened in 1944 and produced the plutonium for the atom bomb that destroyed <LOCATION> Nagasaki </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, in 1945. `` A lot of Iodine 131 was released into the atmosphere at <LOCATION> Hanford </LOCATION>,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON>, assistant director of the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Injury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>, which is doing the study He said research in <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Marshall </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> indicated Iodine 131 can cause thyroid problems. Records of the Hanford leak and the size of the dose were not released until a <LOCATION> Spokane </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, environmental group obtained them in 1986 under the Freedom of Information Act. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last month authorized the study, which <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON> said may take 5 years and cost up to $ 6 million. He said there is no proof yet that there have been long-range damaging effects from the radiation spill. `` It's all anecdotal so far,'' he said. `` The most difficult task will be to find the people, to reassemble the populations and try and track them down.'' He said the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> will use birth and school records to try to find people who lived downwind, to the west, of the nuclear reservation in <LOCATION> Richland </LOCATION> in southeastern <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state. `` That will be our hardest job,'' he said. `` I imagine they have spread out all over the place.'' He said Iodine 131 has a radioactive half-life of only eight days, thus deteriorates quickly and does not linger in the environment and remain a problem. Some radioactive materials are thought to remain dangerous for centuries. The <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION>, which owns the reservation, also is trying to determine the size of the dose nearby residents may have received. There are nine nuclear reactors at <LOCATION> Hanford </LOCATION> and eight are closed permanently. The ninth was placed on `` cold standby'' earlier this year after the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> decided not to restart it after safety improvements were completed. A plutonium processing plant continues to operate. Last May, about 50 people who lived near <LOCATION> Hanford </LOCATION> met in <LOCATION> Spokane </LOCATION> to discuss possible related health problems. June Casey of <LOCATION> Oakland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, a student at <ORGANIZATION> Whitman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Walla </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Walla </LOCATION> in December 1949, when high levels of Iodine 131 were released, said she soon developed an underactive thyroid and lost her hair, which never grew back. <PERSON> Lois </PERSON> <PERSON> Camp </PERSON>, a third-generation farmer who grew up near <LOCATION> Hanford </LOCATION>, said she and her entire family had been stricken with thyroid and cancer problems. She said she has had cancer twice in the past eight years and that her oldest son developed a bone tumor two years ago.
</TEXT>
