<FIRST>r a AM-AIDS-Fatherhood     10-17 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS-Fatherhood,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syracuse AIDS Researcher Says It's Too Early to Make Conclusions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A researcher experimenting with a new, more sensitive test for the AIDS virus said Monday that the virus does not appear to be carried in sperm cells. That discovery could eventually mean that men with AIDS could father children by separating their sperm cells from infected semen and using those cells for artificial insemination. Semen, which is ejaculated, is made up of both sperm cells and seminal fluid. But Dr. <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Poisez </PERSON>, a researcher at the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Syracuse </LOCATION>, said it's a discovery that needs more study. `` All we're saying is that we have a test that's so good we can detect these things and now we need to do some very carefully conducted clinical tests,'' <PERSON> Poisez </PERSON> said. He said he would n't recommend that men infected with AIDS attempt to pursue fatherhood through artificial insemination and he does n't think fertility clinics or in vitro centers would agree to try this without further testing. <PERSON> Poisez </PERSON> said determining whether the AIDS virus is carried inside a sperm cell is one of many studies to exploit a new means of testing for the AIDS virus. The new technique, developed by <ORGANIZATION> Cetus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Emeryville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, uses a chemical reaction, called a polymerase chain reaction, to amplify genetic material _ such as that from the AIDS virus _ a million times, making it easier to detect. <PERSON> Poisez </PERSON> said the test is faster, more accurate and cheaper than some current AIDS tests. Another finding with the new test, <PERSON> Poisez </PERSON> said, is a decline in the number of men with AIDS who have the virus in their semen. Other researchers using the test have documented similar findings, he said. <PERSON> Poisez </PERSON> said he has looked at 500 semen samples over the past four or five years, and that over that period, even with a more sensitive test, the number of samples containing the virus has fallen. Initially, about 75 percent of the men had the virus in their semen, but recently <PERSON> Poisez </PERSON> said researchers have found the virus in just 20 percent of homosexual men who had similar characteristics as the initial group. `` We think this is because they have fewer white blood cells in their semen,'' said <PERSON> Poisez </PERSON>. `` As a result of safe sex and better care, we believe the amount of infections and level of inflammation has been reduced.'' Without the infections and inflammations, the number of white blood cells decreases, <PERSON> Poisez </PERSON> said. This is another finding that needs to be studied, but <PERSON> Poisez </PERSON> said it could eventually mean that researchers could determine when it's especially dangerous to have even safe sex. He said researchers at the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> are currently studying whether the test can be used to determine: _ how effective about six or seven AIDS-fighting drugs are by measuring how quickly they are reducing the number of AIDS-infected cells in the body. _ whether some mothers infected with AIDS would be better candidates for pre-natal use of AIDS-fighting drugs. _ If there are particular times when it's more likely for an unusually large number of AIDS-infected cells to be present in the semen.
</TEXT>
