<HEAD>$7 Million Awarded for 19 AIDS Care Facilities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government announced the award of nearly $ 7 million for construction of health care facilities specifically for AIDS patients on Monday, the first federal money to be directed for such programs. `` The awards went to facilities that were able to demonstrate a comprehensive, cost-effective approach to providing care,'' <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Otis </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON> said in a statement. `` A variety of traditional and nontraditional facilities received the funds, which are to be regarded as seed money.'' With nearly 300,000 people expected to be suffering from AIDS within three years _ compared with about 75,000 diagnosed so far _ a major challenge facing the health care industry is for cost-effective ways to care for such patients. AIDS sufferers often are not in constant need of the costly care supplied by acute-care hospitals, yet are too sick to be cared for at home. The grants announced Monday were to 19 facilities in nine states to renovate or construct non-acute care intermediate and long-term care facilities for patients with AIDS _ acquired immune deficiency syndrome. The nine states are <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON> said the grant recipients had to guarantee that a reasonable volume of services would be provided to patients unable to pay and that services must be made available to all people living or working in a facility's service area. The grant receipients are: _ <ORGANIZATION> Phoenix </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shanti </OR