<SECOND>AM-Nobel-Researchers,0531</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nobel Winners Say Helping the Sick is Their Reward</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RESEARCH TRIANGLE PARK, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> researchers who won the Nobel prize for medicine Monday said the best reward for their work was seeing people overcome disease with the medicines they developed. `` There's nothing that gives you a lift like seeing somebody get better from a serious disease,'' said biochemist <PERSON> Gertrude </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Elion </PERSON>. `` The Nobel is something that is going to disappear in a few days. But the other -LRB- seeing patients recover -RRB- is permanent. `` Not taking anything away from the Nobel prize, but the prize is recognition, not reward,'' she said. `` The reward is seeing the improvement your work makes.'' `` I'm pleased more for my descendants than I am for myself,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitchings </PERSON>, a colleague of Ms. <PERSON> Elion </PERSON>'s at <ORGANIZATION> Wellcome </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` I've had a lot of honors, but the most important honors for me have been meeting patients whose lives have been saved or whose children's lives have been saved by drugs I've invented. <PERSON> Hitchings </PERSON>, 83, and Ms. <PERSON> Elion </PERSON>, 70, began collaborating 44 years ago, and have developed drugs for use against leukemia, malaria, gout, organ transplant rejection, herpes virus infections and bacterial infections. Both carry the title scientist emeritus and are officially retired but come to the lab daily. The Nobel Assembly at <ORGANIZATION> Karolinska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> said their ideas also paved the way for development of azidothymidine, or AZT, which is the best documented drug so far in the treatment of acquired immune deficiency syndrome and the only one approved for use in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The two <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> scientists share the $ 390,000 prize with Sir <ORGANIZATION> James </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> W. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> King </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. His research led to a beta blocker drug for heart disease and a drug for peptic ulcers. Ms. <PERSON> Elion </PERSON> said she had not known she had been nominated for the prize and had never seriously considered that she might win it. `` The only people who thought I might get it was my family,'' she said. `` When I got the first call from a reporter about 6:30 a.m., I told him I thought it was a practical joke and not a very funny one.'' Although she officially retired five years ago, she makes daily trips to <ORGANIZATION> Burroughs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wellcome </ORGANIZATION> to consult with other researchers. `` What's the use of retiring?'' she said. `` If you do n't have anything to contribute anymore, people will tell you. But as long as you can make a contribution, you should.'' Ms. <PERSON> Elion </PERSON> has worked at <ORGANIZATION> Wellcome </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> since 1944 and as a senior research chemist since 1950. Since 1983, she has been a scientist emeritus at the laboratory and a research professor of pharmacology at <ORGANIZATION> Duke </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Hitchings </PERSON>, after teaching at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, joined <ORGANIZATION> Burroughs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wellcome </ORGANIZATION> in 1942. He became its research director in 1955 and retired in 1975 as vice president for research. He was a director of the company from 1968 to 1984 and is president of the <ORGANIZATION> Burroughs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wellcome </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>, a non-profit organization that supports academic research.
