<HEAD>Federal Judge Rules Comatose Patient May Have Feeding Tubes
Removed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A comatose woman has a constitutional right to have her feeding tubes removed, despite objections by a state attorney that she would starve to death, a federal judge ruled Monday. An individual has a constitutional right to control fundamental medical decisions affecting one's own body, even if that will result in death, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boyle </PERSON> said. `` Medical ethics incorporates the principle that the patient, not the health care provider, determines what the course of care should be,'' the judge said. <PERSON> Marcia </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>, 49, has been in a coma since Jan. 4, 1986, when a blood vessel burst in her brain. She had told her husband and relatives on several occasions that, if stricken, she would not want to be kept alive by artificial means, <PERSON> Boyle </PERSON>'s opinion noted. Although she breathes on her own, doctors agree she suffered massive brain damage and is in a `` persistent vegetative state,'' <PERSON> Boyle </PERSON>'s decision said. The case attracted national attention last year when <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON> <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gelineau </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diocese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Providence </ORGANIZATION> approved a theologian's opinion that it was morally permissible to withdraw Mrs. <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>'s nourishment. That opinion, which has been criticized by other moral theologians, said Mrs. <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>'s feeding was `` circumventing'' the dying process. Her husband and guardian, <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>, asked to have her feeding tube removed in March 1987. Officials of <ORGANIZATION> Rhode </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Island </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZ