minor editing to trim</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 First Lady <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> expressed regret Monday that she failed to heed the advice of <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> lawyers that she formally disclose her borrowing of gowns and other designer apparel. But her press secretary and a government ethics spokesman said there was no legal requirement that she do so. Press Secetary <PERSON> Elaine </PERSON> <PERSON> Crispen </PERSON> acknowledged that Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had reported such loans when the issue first arose in November 1981, saying the first lady then decided `` to err on the side'' of compliance with the law. Since 1982, Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has continued to borrow and return items without reporting the transactions, Mrs. <PERSON> Crispen </PERSON> said, even though <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> lawyers originally had recommended disclosure as a precautionary measure. `` Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> regrets that she failed to heed counsel's advice,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Crispen </PERSON> said in a formal statement late Monday `` Nevetheless, no reporting rules or laws were violated.'' A spokesman for the Office of Government Ethics confirmed that the office had supported a conclusion of then-White House Counsel Fred Fielding in 1982 that such reporting was not required under the Ethics in Government Act of 1978. `` The apparel Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> received was either paid for, given to her personally as gifts by old friends and not subject to reporting, or loaned to her and returned. All reporting requirements were met,'' the statement released by Mrs. <PERSON> Crispen </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>, a spokesman for the ethics office, said officials there agreed with Fielding's contention that no reporting was required under the act _ and said that Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has been operating under that guidance s