<HEAD>Lawmakers Complain Philippines Settled for Too Little</HEAD>
<HEAD>with AM-US-Philippines, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lawmakers complained Monday that the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> settled for too little in a pact on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military bases and warned the terms could boost those who want the facilities closed when the lease expires. President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> urged the public to wait for more details before judging the new agreement, which was signed Monday afternoon in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> by Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> and the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>' Foreign Secretary <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Manglapus </PERSON>. The pact sets the terms for the remaining two years of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> lease on the bases, which expires in 1991. Under the terms, the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> will get $ 962 million in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid in exchange for use of the bases. The negotiations were technically a review of an existing bases agreement that the Aquino government never hinted at canceling. But tension between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and its former colony were high because of bargaining over the aid package as well as nuclear and other issues. Opposition Sen. <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ponce </PERSON> <PERSON> Enrile </PERSON> said Monday the upper chamber should have the chance to ratify the agreement as if it were a treaty because `` there are rights and obligations growing from it.'' He cited a constitutional provision which says no treaty or international agreement shall be valid without the concurrence of two-thirds of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. The Aquino administration has not indicated that the agreement needs <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> approval. Sen. <PERSON> Ernesto </PERSON> <PERSON> Maceda </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said