<HEAD>U.N. Officials Say U.S. Still Will Withhold Some Dues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will continue withholding some of its dues to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> despite President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s pledge last month that they would be paid, <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officials said Monday. The officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> would retain $ 59 million in dues to force the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> to adopt an austerity budget. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Eckhard </PERSON> said the withholding of funds will endanger <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peacekeeping projects, such as military observers in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and possible future missions to <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and other areas. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> on Sept. 13 that he would release the $ 188 million in dues owed for last year and this year and added he was satisfied with the organization's progress on budgetary and administrative reforms. The $ 188 million is $ 44 million from the previous fiscal year and $ 144 million for the current fiscal year. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> paid $ 15 million in September and on Friday it gave the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> $ 85.6 million. That still leaves more than $ $ 87 million from the $ 188 million owed. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had said the full amount would be paid by the end of the year. But the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officials said <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> informed <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> that $ 59 million would be frozen until the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>'s main financial committee, the <ORGANIZATION> Fifth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, adopts an austerity budget recommended last month by a subcommittee. Even if the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> pays all $ 188 million it will still owe millions more to the world organization in funds withheld during earlier years. Friday's payment reduced the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> arrears to the regular budget to $ 366.3 million. And <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officials estimate <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> owes about $ 300 million more for unpaid assessments for other projects including peacekeeping forces and payments to <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> special agencies. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> last month pledged a `` multi-year'' payment plan for all the back dues. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Undersecretary-General <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> has said the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> told him the payments would be on a three-to-five-year plan. Since <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> took office nearly eight years ago his administration has harshly criticized the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nation </LOCATION>, accusing it of having an anti-Western bias and of bureaucracy and waste. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is assessed one-fourth of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION>'s regular budget, and was supposed to pay $ 212 million this fiscal year but <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> only appropriated $ 144 million. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officials have said that continued withholding of funds could force the world body to close in November. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> has no reserve funds and operates by spending dues it collects almost as soon as it receives them. <PERSON> Eckhard </PERSON> said so far the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> has collected only a fraction of the $ 35.7 million it assessed its members for the first three month of operations of the <ORGANIZATION> Iran-Iraq </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Observer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>.
