<HEAD>American Instruments May Ride into Space on a Soviet Rocket, Tass
Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> officials are discussing possibly installing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> scientific instruments on a Soviet spacecraft as part of a joint superpower project to monitor damage to the Earth's ozone layer, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. The Soviet news agency quoted the head of a <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> delegation to recent superpower talks on space, <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Chernikov </PERSON>, as saying the discussions in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> dealt with the launching of a U.S.-made spectrometer on the Soviet Meteor-3 satellite in 1990-91. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Redmond </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, confirmed on Monday that a <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> official is now in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> for discussions on placing a spectrometer on a Soviet satellite to monitor the ozone layer. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> equipment has been used aboard a Soviet spacecraft in the past, but <PERSON> Redmond </PERSON> said this venture would be the first in which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would actually supervise its own equipment by working with the Soviets. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said the goal of the joint program was to measure the Earth's ozone layer from space and calculate regional ozone depletion, especially over <LOCATION> Antarctica </LOCATION>. `` The program has been worked out in accordance with the agreement, reached at the Soviet-U.S. summit in 1988, on expanding cooperation within the framework of the Soviet-American agreement on space exploration,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> quoted <PERSON> Chernikov </PERSON> as saying. He said the project also would help implement the goals of the international <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> convention for protection of the ozone layer. The next meeting of Soviet and American specialists is scheduled for January in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said.
