 The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Editors </ORGANIZATION> on Monday criticized the South African government for `` consistent and arbitrary'' censorship of the press in that country. The <ORGANIZATION> ASNE </ORGANIZATION>, in a letter to South African President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, expressed `` urgent concern'' over a warning issued to the Weekly Mail by <PERSON> Stoffel </PERSON> <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, minister of Home Affairs and Communications. The action `` reinforces the fear we expressed in our last communication that it is the intention of the government to cripple, one by one, any inconvenient publication,'' <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Kovach </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> ASNE </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communication </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said in the letter. `` Censorship for whatever reason is repugnant to any people, but it is especially so to those who profess to have some voice in governing themselves,'' said <PERSON> Kovach </PERSON>, editor of the Atlanta Journal and Constitution. `` At this most critical time in the spread of the notion of a free press in the world it is especially deplorable that the government of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> chooses to continue its course down the road of darkness and fear,'' <PERSON> Kovach </PERSON> wrote. He urged the South African government not to take further steps against the Weekly Mail and to restore the right to publish to other publications that have been shut down.
