<BYLINE>By DICK PETTYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal grand jury indicted Rep. <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> on perjury charges Monday, accusing the two-term <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> congressman of lying during a money laundering investigation. <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON>, locked in what has been called one of the country's dirtiest congressional re-election battles, pleaded innocent to all counts during an afternoon arraignment and was free on his own recognizance He said he hoped to bring the case to trial next Monday in order to clear his name by the Nov. 8 general election. `` When I am exonerated, obviously the only issue that remains is whether the 4th District wants a Dukakis liberal or a <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> conservative,'' he told reporters at <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> said he would resign if he were convicted of the charges, even though not required to by law. He said he expects to serve a jail term if found guilty. He said he would step down `` because under the circumstances, I do n't think it would be fair to the voters of the 4th District'' to remain in office. His Democratic opponent, former `` Dukes of Hazzard'' television actor <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, commented, `` I feel concern for the congressman and for his family at this point. ... It is a matter for the courts to decide.'' The 10-count indictment accused <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> of lying to the grand jury last Feb. 2 during its investigation of a proposed $ 850,000 home mortgage loan the congressman had discussed with an <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> businessman and an undercover agent posing as a financier. Among other things, the indictment charged that <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> lied when he told the grand jury he did not go to authorities to report the loan negotiations, because, he said, `` I never satisfied myself of anything with respect to criminality.'' The indictment also charged <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> lied when he said there had never been discussions about trying to conceal the trail of the money, and that he lied when he denied having been specifically informed by the undercover agent that the source of the loan could be illicit drug money. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Barr </PERSON> said that if convicted, <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> could be sentenced to five years in prison and fined $ 10,000 on each count. <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON>, who had been notified of the pending indictment in advance, announced Sunday night that he expected to be indicted and said he was excited by the prospect because it would give him a chance to clear his name. He said he would waive a number of rights, including the right to charge the government with misconduct, so the case could go to trial next Monday. <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> said he would act as his own attorney. <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> entered his innocent plea before <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Magistrate <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Harper </PERSON>, who then assigned the case to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Vining </PERSON>. <PERSON> Vining </PERSON> had previously been scheduled to try <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> businessman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> LeChasney </PERSON> and a second person accused of money laundering next Monday. <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> said there were indications <PERSON> LeChasney </PERSON> and the second man might step aside and allow <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON>'s case to be tried ahead of their cases. <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON>, who defeated <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> in 1986, this year has made an issue of <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>' arrest record, including a conviction for assaulting his wife. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> has said the incidents occurred during a bout with alcoholism that ended in 1977. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, who starred as `` Cooter'' in the long-running television series, `` The Dukes of Hazzard,'' once suggested that <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> submit to drug tests, insinuating the congressman's behavior was unstable. The indictment stems from negotiations <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> undertook last year with LeChasney to finance a mortgage loan for his $ 1.2 million home. LeChasney, who has since been indicted on money-laundering charges, introduced <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> to <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Mullaney </PERSON>, an undercover <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> agent posing as a money broker. In June, <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> newspapers obtained several secretly made government tape recordings of conversations among <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON>, <PERSON> LeChasney </PERSON> and the undercover agent. The tapes showed that <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> continued to pursue negotiations for an $ 850,000 loan after being told that the source might be drug money he would be helping to launder. He accepted a $ 150,000 check as the first installment on the loan, but returned it uncashed three days later, saying he was suspicious of LeChasney's business dealings. <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> has since apologized for his role in the negotiations, calling it a mistake in judgment but insisting there was no wrongdoing.
