<HEAD>Fan Failure Causes Evacuation Of 100 At Nuclear Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AIKEN, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A malfunctioning fan in a plutonium-processing area caused the evacuation of about 100 employees at the <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> Plant Monday, but officials said there was no contamination of the workers or the atmosphere. The fan broke down at 2:46 p.m., and was restarted about 30 minutes later, said plant spokesman <PERSON> Cliff </PERSON> <PERSON> Webb </PERSON>. The cause of the equipment failure was under investigation. The exhaust fan is used to pull fresh air from the outside through the building and out to filters that trap any radioactive material. The air flow serves to remove any releases of contamination from the building. But a fan failure could produce a reverse air flow, which could allow contamination to accumulate in the building or be forced outside. The amount of contamination would depend on how much plutonium was being processed when such an accident occurred. Officials will not discuss specifics on plutonium production. A backup fan normally would have been activated, but the second unit was out of service for routine maintenance, <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> said. Meanwhile, about 700 employees elsewhere in <LOCATION> F-Area </LOCATION>, where plutonium is refined for use in nuclear weapons, were detained about an hour while an inventory of nuclear materials was completed. Such inventories are routinely conducted, <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> said.
