 Choreographer <PERSON> Rallou </PERSON> <PERSON> Manou </PERSON>, widely recognized for introducing modern dance in <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, has died of a stroke at the age of 73. Ms. <PERSON> Manou </PERSON>, who directed the <PERSON> Hellenic </PERSON> <PERSON> Chorodrama </PERSON> that she helped set up with leading Greek artists in 1951, died Saturday. The daughter of a wealthy Greek army officer, Ms. <PERSON> Manou </PERSON> studied dance in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> before working under American modern dance pioneer <PERSON> Martha </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> at <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in the 1940s. Works presented by the <ORGANIZATION> Hellenic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chorodrama </ORGANIZATION>, of which Ms. <PERSON> Manou </PERSON> was the principal choreographer, blended avant-garde dance forms with classical drama. She insisted that the dance group, which performed each summer in the open-air Lycabettus theater in <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION>, be inspired by Greek tradition. `` I do n't think ballet is the kind, type or spirit of dance that can best express <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>,'' she once said. `` Modern dance is the best form and also the one which comes nearest to ancient Greek dance.''
