<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A tropical storm off the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> coast reached hurricane force Monday with winds of more than 80 mph as the system gathered strength over open water, forecasters said. Hurricane <PERSON> Joan </PERSON>, the fifth hurricane of the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> season, was upgraded from tropical storm status Monday night and could intensify as it moves away from the Colombian coast and into the western <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>, the National Hurricane Center reported. The storm's winds, which had dropped to 45 mph Sunday, rose to at least 80 mph in an area northwest of the center and 75 mph winds over most of the system, just above the minimum 74 mph hurricane level. At 9 p.m. EDT, <PERSON> Joan </PERSON>'s center was near latitude 11.9 north and longitude 74.1 west, or just west of the <LOCATION> Guajira </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, and 520 miles east of the island of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Andres </LOCATION> off the coast of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. The hurricane was moving west at 10 mph and was expected to continue that motion through Tuesday. Four to 8 inches of rain is forecast along <PERSON> Joan </PERSON>'s path. `` It's a straight shot to <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, but it's not there yet. There is no threat for the next 60 hours or so,'' said center forecaster <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Gross </PERSON>. <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> became the 10th named system of the 1988 <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> hurricane season Oct. 11 when top winds passed the minimum 39 mph mark to qualify for classification as a tropical storm. There have been four other hurricanes so far this season, including Hurricane Gilbert, which left more than 300 people dead and caused billions of dollars in damage as it tore through <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>