<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> reached for the common touch on Monday, visiting a metal factory, a diner and a bowling alley as he tried to reinvigorate a faltering presidential campaign. `` I want to be a president who stands up and fights for American companies, American products and American workers,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said, depicting Republican rival <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> as the candidate of complacency. The <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor embraced the role of underdog as polls in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and elsewhere showed him losing ground since last week's presidential debate. An <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> poll reported <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> leading 55 percent to 38 percent, but <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> disputed the fundings. `` Well I can only tell you that there are other polls that say very different things about where we are and where the race is,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> told an interviewer for a <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> television station. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, in a series of interviews, described the race as `` very tight'' and said, `` the business of polls is really having a terrible effect'' on the campaign process. `` Now we've got a new set of numbers that has absolutely no relationship to anything that we have or other polls have, so you spend two or three days'' answering answering questions about it. He declined to say what his internal campaign polling shows. The governor's day was designed to counter criticism that he has failed to connect emotionally with middle class voters, particularly those in the industrial states. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> ended his day more than 12 hours after he began at a rally in <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION> attended by blacks and he took a veiled shot at <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. `` Something 