<SECOND>PM-Japan-Archaeology, Adv 19,0598</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wednesday, Oct. 19, or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>6th-Century Coffin Yields Evidence of Korean Cultural Influence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By K.P. HONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Japanese archaeologists say a 6th-century stone coffin opened in a previously untouched tomb contains dozens of treasures showing a strong likelihood of Korean cultural influence in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. A government research team lifted the two-ton lid off the vermillion-colored coffin Oct. 8 at the Fujinoki Tumulus, or mound, in <LOCATION> Nara </LOCATION> prefecture, the heartland of ancient <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. Japanese newspapers and television have given the discovery extensive coverage while the archaeologists carefully drain water from the coffin to retrieve the encrusted articles. They say the treasures include at least three swords, a pair of gilt-bronze shoes, a golden necklace, earrings, ornaments and other accessories. The coffin also contains human bones and remnants of cloth. Officials at <ORGANIZATION> Kashihara </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Archaeological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Nara </LOCATION> prefecture, in western <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, say recovery of the relics and remains will take several weeks. The identity of the person buried in the tomb is not known. Professor <PERSON> Kyoichi </PERSON> <PERSON> Arimitsu </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Kyoto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, who directed the <ORGANIZATION> Kashihara </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in 1980-1984, said the relics were believed to be from one of <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s three ancient kingdoms _ <LOCATION> Silla </LOCATION>, Paekche or <LOCATION> Koguryo </LOCATION>. `` They are similar to those found in tumuluses in the <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>,'' he said in a telephone interview after inspecting the excavation. <PERSON> Kazu </PERSON> <PERSON> Uehara </PERSON>, a professor of art history at <ORGANIZATION> Seijo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, agrees with <PERSON> Arimitsu </PERSON>. `` When a set of harness was found at the Fujinoki Tumulus three years ago, some people disagreed with my view that it might have come from <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` They said the harness looked more like Chinese. `` The remains in the stone coffin, I believe, will correct their theory. I know, of course, there are similarities between ancient Chinese culture and that of <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. However, they are not the same. For instance, hexagonal ornaments extracted from the stone coffin have been found only in Korean tumuluses. `` There are some Japanese scholars who would hesitate to accept the fact that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> received more cultural heritage from <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> than <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. ... The tendency, I believe, stems from an attitude of looking down on a small country like <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>.'' The tomb and mound date from the Yamato period, which ran from early in the Christian era through 710. <ORGANIZATION> Yamato </ORGANIZATION> is the ancient name for mountainous <LOCATION> Nara </LOCATION> prefecture, where the first unified state in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> was based. Members of its ruling class were buried in mounds. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> made their first peaceful contacts during the Yamato period and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> began its long history of adopting and adapting the cultures of others. Writing in Chinese characters was imported from <LOCATION> Paekche </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> in 285. In the next 300 years, through contacts with <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, the Japanese learned of the formidable and advanced culture of the Asian mainland. <PERSON> Arimitsu </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Fujinoki </LOCATION> mound was believed to have been created between 551 and 575. It is about 600 yards from the <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> temple <LOCATION> Horyuji </LOCATION>, built between 601 and 607 in the town of <LOCATION> Ikaruga </LOCATION>, 8 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Nara </LOCATION>. Excavation of the mound, which is 30 feet high, began in 1985. About 3,500 relics have been found, including exquisite gold and bronze objects, in addition to the stone coffin. Archaeologists viewed the coffin's interior in June, using a flexible instrument with a lens on the end, and set up a chain-and-pulley mechanism to raise the heavy, peaked cover. End Adv for Wed Oct. 19
