<HEAD>American Victim Of China's Past Helps It with Future</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Sidney </PERSON> <PERSON> Rittenberg </PERSON> came to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> as a young idealist and his reward was 16 years in prison. Now he helps other foreigners find keys to the doors of commerce in his adopted land. <PERSON> Rittenberg </PERSON>, 67, is president of <PERSON> Kamsky </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rittenberg </PERSON>, a consulting firm that helps foreign clients, most of their American, get information and access to Chinese officials. Since establishing the firm a year ago, <PERSON> Rittenberg </PERSON> has found markets and <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> partners for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> makers of gas turbines, pencils, jeans and electrical appliances, and guided them through the enigmatic world of Chinese contract negotiations. He has organized tours for such as evangelist <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> and Gov. <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Mabus </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, sometimes acting as interpreter in impeccable Mandarin at meetings with senior Chinese leaders. `` I like the feeling that we're building little bridges,'' he said in an interview. <PERSON> Rittenberg </PERSON> began building his bridges decades ago, with some disastrous consequences. He is a native of <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, and first came to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in 1945, as a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> interpreter after studying Chinese at <LOCATION> Stanford </LOCATION>. Like other young American liberals caught up in the turbulence, <PERSON> Rittenberg </PERSON> was attracted by the zeal and idealism of <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Tse-tung </PERSON>'s revolutionaries `` I was taken with the idea they were going to build a new kind of just, democratic socialist society,'' he said. After leaving the Army he decided to stay in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, at the urging of <PERSON> Chou </PERSON> <PERSON> En-lai </PERSON> and other leaders, to help establish an English-language radio service. When Chinese authorities put him in the back of a truck going to <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> in 1949, he thought he was being enlisted to help negotiate relations between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>'s new Communist government. `` I was euphoric,'' he said. Instead, <PERSON> Rittenberg </PERSON> was imprisoned on charges of being an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> spy. He learned later that Soviet dictator <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> demanded his arrest, claiming <PERSON> Rittenberg </PERSON> was an accomplice of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> journalist <PERSON> Anna </PERSON> <PERSON> Louise </PERSON> <PERSON> Strong </PERSON>, who had been arrested in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> for spying. She and <PERSON> Rittenberg </PERSON> were collaborating on a biography of <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>. Six years in prison followed, the first of them in an unlighted room with black cloth over the windows. When he was released and cleared of wrongdoing in 1955, `` <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> apologized to me,'' he said. `` They really felt bad about it and took me into the family.'' Back at Radio <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, he was made privy to material seldom revealed to outsiders. `` That was power, access to inside information,'' he said in the interview. His world collapsed once more during the Cultural Revolution of 1966-76. Again he was deceived. He said he thought the Cultural Revolution, with which <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> dislodged the entrenched bureaucracy, `` was a great day, a kind of town hall democracy.'' But the radical leftists who gained power revived the old spying charges and jailed him in 1968. He spent 10 years in solitary and his <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> wife, <PERSON> Yulin </PERSON>, was sentenced to three years in a labor camp. `` There was only one real issue, keeping your sanity from day to day,'' he said of the lost decade. `` I tried not to be bitter. In solitary, bitterness is the enemy. But who are you going to be sore at? It was the whole system.'' He said he felt freedom was near when he heard <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>'s widow, <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Qing </PERSON>, yelling from a nearby cell. <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON>, who <PERSON> Rittenberg </PERSON> says personally prolonged his prison term, was arrested in late 1976 as ringleader of the notorious `` Gang of Four.'' Again released and again exonerated, he was given a sinecure with the <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION>, helping arrange academic exchanges. In 1979 he returned to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for the first time in 34 years. <PERSON> Rittenberg </PERSON> now spends about half the year in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. His consulting firm has an office in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and he has a home in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, where one of his four children also lives. His hope that Chinese communism would be `` different from the <LOCATION> Russians </LOCATION>, more civilized and democratic,'' dissolved long ago. `` <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> went back on his promises,'' he said, and if the democratic socialism he once envisioned for <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> ever comes, `` it will be nothing resembling <ORGANIZATION> Marxist-Leninist </ORGANIZATION> societies so far.'' After so many years away, <PERSON> Rittenberg </PERSON> said, he finds the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to be a more humane country. `` The leaders of the Chinese revolution did n't understand that if not everyone is protected by law then no one is,'' he said. `` Our forefathers were smart enough to build that into the system.'' <PERSON> Rittenberg </PERSON> worries about corruption in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, where young people `` have no 10 Commandments and no Communist ideology'' and party officials are among the greediest. He said there are `` thieves galore built into the system,'' but believes a `` kind of self-correcting mechanism'' will see <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> through. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` have a special chemistry and there's no reason it should n't cement and grow,'' <PERSON> Rittenberg </PERSON> said. `` I feel kind of good it is happening now.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thu AMs, Oct.20</NOTE>
