<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is a list of key congressional races in which women candidates are raising strong challenges. Also listed are races in which women incumbents are facing stiff challenges. <LOCATION> WISCONSIN </LOCATION>: <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Engeleiter </PERSON>, 36, a Republican state senator with a law degree from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION>, is trailing Democrat <PERSON> Herb </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> in the race to succeed retiring Sen. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON>, a Democrat known for his shoe-string campaigns. Internal polls by both campaigns show <PERSON> Engeleiter </PERSON> about 10 points behind, but she is seeking to capitalize on her experience in state economic matters. <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>, 52, a wealthy businessman and owner of the <ORGANIZATION> Milwaukee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bucks </ORGANIZATION>, is a political novice. Using his own money, <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> is expected to spend up to $ 7 million compared with <PERSON> Engeleiter </PERSON>'s $ 3 million. <LOCATION> CALIFORNIA </LOCATION>: <PERSON> Anna </PERSON> <PERSON> Eschoo </PERSON>, a Democratic <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mateo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> supervisor, is making a strong showing in her bid to fill the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> seat of Rep. <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Konnyu </PERSON>, a one-term Republican who was the only representative to lose in a primary. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>, a political newcomer who teaches law at <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, defeated <PERSON> Konnyu </PERSON> in the primary. Polls show a close race. <LOCATION> COLORADO </LOCATION>: <PERSON> Martha </PERSON> <PERSON> Ezzard </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> state senator who switched parties last year, is challenging incumbent <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Schaefer </PERSON> in a district that includes the <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> suburbs. The environment is an issue. <LOCATION> IDAHO </LOCATION>: <PERSON> Jeanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Givens </PERSON>, a Democratic state legislator, would be the first native <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> women in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> if she unseats incumbent <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Craig </PERSON>, a four-term incumbent. <PERSON> Givens </PERSON> has traveled the length of the state's first district in a bus to solicit votes. <LOCATION> LOUISIANA </LOCATION>: <PERSON> Faye </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, a Democratic lawyer, is in a rematch with Rep. <PERSON> Clyde </PERSON> <PERSON> Holloway </PERSON>, a one-term Republican. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> would become the first black woman elected in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> if she unseats <PERSON> Holloway </PERSON> in the 8th district race. Black registration in the district is about 36 percent. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, who has strong support from <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> stalwarts, was hurt in her 1986 race by revelations that her estranged husband had beat <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> and shot to death the man she had been dating in 1971. <LOCATION> MARYLAND </LOCATION>: First-term Republican <PERSON> Constance </PERSON> <PERSON> Morella </PERSON> is facing a challenge from <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Franchot </PERSON>, a member of the <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> legislature, in <LOCATION> Montgomery </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, a wealthy suburb of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Morella </PERSON> is a moderate Republican who narrowly won a formerly Democratic seat in 1986. <LOCATION> MICHIGAN </LOCATION>: <PERSON> Lana </PERSON> <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON>, a state senator, is trying to oust Rep. <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Pursell </PERSON>, a six-term <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> incumbent in the 2nd district. The disparate district includes <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Arbor </PERSON>, the home of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION>, as well as the <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> suburbs. <LOCATION> NEW </LOCATION> <LOCATION> YORK </LOCATION>: <PERSON> Nita </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowey </PERSON>, former <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> assistant secretary of state, faces incumbent Rep. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> DioGuardi </PERSON>, a Republican, in heavily populated suburban <LOCATION> Westchester </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> outside <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. <PERSON> DioGuardi </PERSON>, an accountant, was first elected by the 20th District in 1986. <LOCATION> NEW </LOCATION> <LOCATION> YORK </LOCATION>: <PERSON> Rosemary </PERSON> <PERSON> Pooler </PERSON>, a former public service commissioner, is running a strong race in the 27th district to succeed Rep. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wortley </PERSON>, a Republican who is retiring. Facing <PERSON> Pooler </PERSON> is <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>, a council member from <LOCATION> Syracuse </LOCATION>. The district is halfway between <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Buffalo </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> NEW </LOCATION> <LOCATION> YORK </LOCATION>: Rep. <PERSON> Louise </PERSON> <PERSON> Slaughter </PERSON>, a Democrat from the 30th district, was the only woman to defeat an incumbent in 1986. She is facing <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bouchard </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION> in the race to keep her seat in what has traditionally been a Republican district. <LOCATION> SOUTH </LOCATION> <LOCATION> CAROLINA </LOCATION>: Rep. <PERSON> Liz </PERSON> <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON>, a first-term incumbent Democrat, has a tough fight to keep her seat in the 4th District where Republicans are strong. Her opponent is <PERSON> Knox </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, a city councilman from <LOCATION> Greenville </LOCATION> who has patterned his positions after those of Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. <LOCATION> WASHINGTON </LOCATION>: <PERSON> Jolene </PERSON> <PERSON> Unsoeld </PERSON>, a Democratic state legislator, is favored to win the seat vacated by Rep. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonker </PERSON>, a Democrat. <PERSON> Unsoeld </PERSON> faces <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Wight </PERSON>, a former aide to Republican Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Warner </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Unsoeld </PERSON>, an avid environmentalist and a mountain climber, lost her husband and her daughter in separate mountain climbing accidents.
