<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At the Movies: ``Clara's Heart,'' ``Imagine: John Lennon''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 `` Clara's Heart'' <PERSON> Clara </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayfield </PERSON> is a brutally direct woman who colors her human relationships with a good deal of common sense, self-righteousness and tenacity. She also has an overwhelming humanity about her, and that specialness attracts people to her like a magnet. The relationship she forges with young <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> is bound to be a memorable screen joining. <PERSON> Clara </PERSON> is a vibrant and rich role, one that could easily turn around <PERSON> Whoopi </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON>'s dismal film career. After such losers as `` Burglar,'' `` Jumpin' Jack Flash'' and `` Fatal Beauty,'' in which the stand-up comic was required to do little more than imitate <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> and be the Butterfly <PERSON> McQueen </PERSON> of the 1980s, <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> finally has a chance to demonstrate her talents as a dramatic actress. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulligan </PERSON> -LRB- `` To Kill a Mockingbird,'' `` Inside Daisy Clover'' -RRB- restrains <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> in his direction of this family melodrama, allowing none of the bits and business that have become the trademarks of her wealth of comic stage characters. That restraint is essential to Clara herself, a Jamaican with a dark secret. <PERSON> Clara </PERSON> enters the lives of the affluent <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> family from <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Shore </LOCATION>, shortly after the crib death of their daughter. <PERSON> Leona </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Quinlan </PERSON> -RRB- and <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> -LRB- MichaelOntkean -RRB- have gone to <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION> to help get over the tragedy. <PERSON> Clara </PERSON> is their hotel maid. She coaxes <PERSON> Leona </PERSON> out of her depression and encourages her to get on with life. <PERSON> Leona </PERSON> decides to bring her back to <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> _ she ca n't quite function without <PERSON> Clara </PERSON>'s island sensibilities. But son <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> takes an immediate dislike to <PERSON> Clara </PERSON> and accuses his parents _ rightfully so _ of bringing her home so they wo n't have to deal with him. The Harts are in the process of a divorce. He has taken up with a hot cutie, and she has taken up with a pretentious bore of a pop shrink -LRB- Spalding Gray -RRB-. <PERSON> Clara </PERSON> eventually wins over <PERSON> David </PERSON> to the point where he'd rather spend his weekends in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> with <PERSON> Clara </PERSON> and her West Indian friends than with his parents. He also picks up <PERSON> Clara </PERSON>'s island patois, to the delight of her friends. But <PERSON> David </PERSON>'s dependency on Clara ultimately leads to her dark revelation. And it is here that the movie falters. There is no build-up to this awful experience in her life, and its unfolding is an abrupt twist. And with the tale, there remain loose ends: Letters hidden in a suitcase and found by <PERSON> David </PERSON> are never explained; the father of <PERSON> Clara </PERSON>'s child also is a mystery. Still, `` Clara's Heart'' is a warm movie with many lessons to tell, if one is willing to listen. Its force is aided by <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON>'s performance and a noteworthy movie debut of <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> as <PERSON> David </PERSON> The <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bros. </ORGANIZATION> release of an <ORGANIZATION> MTM </ORGANIZATION> Entertainment Production features a lilting score by <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Grusin </PERSON>. But Hollywood has yet to learn through its endless quest for authenticity that steel music and calypso are products of <LOCATION> Trinidad </LOCATION>, not <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>, where reggae and soca bloom. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Elfand </PERSON> produced `` Clara's Heart,'' which is rated PG-13. _ By <PERSON> Dolores </PERSON> <PERSON> Barclay </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Editor </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` Imagine: <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lennon </PERSON>'' Rarely has a 20th-century phenomenon been so thoroughly chronicled in every conceivable way as the Beatles. Yet the new documentary `` Imagine: <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lennon </PERSON>'' provides previously unseen material on the most enigmatic of the Beatles, if not any fresh insights. <PERSON> Yoko </PERSON> <PERSON> Ono </PERSON>, <PERSON> Lennon </PERSON>'s ever-protective widow, released 200 hours of tapes and films from their private collection to documentary and miniseries producer <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolper </PERSON> -LRB- `` The Making of the President: 1960,'' `` Roots'' -RRB-. <PERSON> Wolper </PERSON> and producer-director <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Solt </PERSON> culled through the material and also searched for newsreels and TV appearances. The documentary material was combined with new interviews with <PERSON> Yoko </PERSON> <PERSON> Ono </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lennon </PERSON>'s first wife, <PERSON> Cynthia </PERSON>, sons <PERSON> Julian </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sean </PERSON>, and various associates of <PERSON> Lennon </PERSON>. None of the three surviving Beatles was interviewed. `` Imagine'' provides a gold mine for Beatle lovers and especially those who revere <PERSON> Lennon </PERSON>, who was slain outside his apartment in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> by a crazed fan in 1980. But the film provides marginal entertainment for the average moviegoer. Documentaries are never easy to endure in a theater. `` Imagine'' is no exception, despite the great skill that went into its making. There are some riveting moments. The most scarifying comes when <PERSON> John </PERSON> and <PERSON> Yoko </PERSON> encounter cartoonist <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Capp </PERSON> -LRB- `` L'il Abner'' -RRB- during the <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION> Bed-in for Peace, a meeting as deadly in its way as a mongoose's minuet with two cobras. The <ORGANIZATION> Lennons </ORGANIZATION>' penchant for shock is demonstrated in a nude love-making scene which was filmed two weeks before he died, intended for a music video. It is antiseptically graphic, hardly erotic at all. Director <PERSON> Solt </PERSON> has capably maintained the kind of pace established in the trend-setting Beatles feature `` A Hard Day's Night. Only in the final sequence does the film falter. <PERSON> Lennon </PERSON>'s murder and the outpouring of grief from his candle-holding fans is protracted into a kind of deification that hardly suits the subject There is commentary by family and friends, and <PERSON> Lennon </PERSON>'s own voice narrates much of `` Imagine.'' Whether he was excessively narcissistic or merely had a exceptional sense of history, posterity should be grateful for his extensive record-keeping. How valuable it would be to have such records of <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Dean </PERSON>, <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON>, <PERSON> Elvis </PERSON> <PERSON> Presley </PERSON> and other icons. The <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bros. </ORGANIZATION> release was co-produced by <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Egan </PERSON> and written by <PERSON> Egan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Solt </PERSON>. Rated R for nudity and language. Running time: 103 minutes. _ By <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
