<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 `` Talk Is Cheap'' -LRB- Island -RRB- _ <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Richards </PERSON> If <PERSON> Mick </PERSON> <PERSON> Jagger </PERSON>'s solo records are <PERSON> Jagger </PERSON> without the <ORGANIZATION> Rolling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stones </ORGANIZATION>, conversely, and somewhat symmetrically, <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Richards </PERSON>' first solo effort is the Stones without <PERSON> Jagger </PERSON> <PERSON> Richards </PERSON> is n't much of a singer, but he manages a listenable rasp on a series of tunes that would n't exactly tax <PERSON> Caruso </PERSON>. This is a tough rock musicians' record, anyway, starting with <PERSON> Richards </PERSON>' patented take-no-prisoners guitar backed by a stellar cast of studio musicians, including <PERSON> Bernie </PERSON> <PERSON> Worrell </PERSON> on organ, <PERSON> Waddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Wachtel </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mick </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> -LRB- former Stone -RRB- on guitars, <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Keys </PERSON> and <PERSON> Macco </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> on various saxes, plus the <ORGANIZATION> Memphis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Horns </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Charley </PERSON> <PERSON> Drayton </PERSON> is on bass most of the time, <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> drums and <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Neville </PERSON> keyboards. <PERSON> Sarah </PERSON> <PERSON> Dash </PERSON> sings background. <PERSON> Patti </PERSON> <PERSON> Scialfa </PERSON> -LRB- E Street Band and the Boss' main squeeze -RRB- is on one cut. All the songs were co-written by <PERSON> Richards </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>. `` Take It Hard'' and `` Struggle'' are especially worth blasting loud enough to enrage the neighbors. <PERSON> Richards </PERSON> makes a mistake on `` Make No Mistake'' with his impersonation of <PERSON> Peggy </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> on steroids. Dash comes in to save it, though, giving <PERSON> Richards </PERSON> a Tom Waits-like charm by comparison. They team again on the wonderfully soulful `` Rockawhile.'' `` Locked Away'' is a real pretty tune. <PERSON> Richards </PERSON> should hire someone else to sing it. By the last cut, `` It Means a Lot,'' it seems <PERSON> Richards-Jordan </PERSON> had run out of ideas. But the closer of Side 1, `` You Do n't Move Me,'' is another four-star effort that could apply to anyone you know who needs a verbal thrashing but here, it was obviously meant for <PERSON> Jagger </PERSON>: `` You lost the feeling, got so appealing. Why do you think you think you got no friends? You drove'em all ` round the bend Ah, yeah, you do n't move me anymore. ... It's no longer funny, it's bigger than money, you just do n't move me anymore.'' As the record says, `` Talk Is Cheap,'' so you better be able to move'em yourself. And most of the time <PERSON> Richards </PERSON> does, with room to spare. _ By <PERSON> Kathryn </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` Tighten Up Vol. 88'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ Big Audio Dynamite <PERSON> Mick </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, once the fiery guitarist of punk heroes The Clash, now seems a little like a roguish older brother. He lectures a lot, mostly about respecting the rights of others. His music, once loud and brash, is more melodic and _ dare we say _ nearly laid back. The cover of his group's new album shows him dressed in a tuxedo, although with a lipstick stain on his face and clutching a wine bottle. Big Audio Dynamite's first album a few years back was an exciting synthesis of rock and urban rhythms, mixed in with the `` found sounds'' of old movie clips. The second album was a less exciting take on the same idea. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> and his usual writing partner, <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Letts </PERSON>, are neither melodically adventurous nor particularly good singers, so many B.A.D. songs tend to sound the same. The group needed to stretch out a bit, and for the most part do it successfully on `` Tighten Up Vol. 88'' <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>' old group wanted to save the world, now the ambitions are scaled back. `` No one gets 10 out of 10,'' he sings on `` Other 99,'' `` You got ta strive for five.'' In `` Funny Names,'' he sings, `` You're not like me. I'm not like you. Do n't mean we ca n't get along.'' Their utopian outlook would sound naive if it was n't so good-natured. B.A.D. does n't take itself too seriously, unlike the Clash. One of the best songs here, `` Just Play Music,'' rejects rock star trappings and suggests good music is really quite simple. That's not just a lyrical approach. B.A.D. uses some familiar <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Berry </PERSON> riffs, borrows from the old standard `` Battle of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>'' and generally goes for straightforward rock on this album. But many of the songs are sweetened by synthesizers and few have a particularly hard edge. Big Audio Dynamite can consider this a rebound from the sophomore slump. _ By <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Bauder </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` Hot Water'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> MCA </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Buffett </PERSON> There was a time when <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Buffett </PERSON> sang cleverly, and sometimes even movingly, about everything from life, love and loneliness to cheeseburgers, gas station robberies and the sea. That was more than a decade ago now, before <PERSON> Buffett </PERSON> began a long, sad slide that finds him, again, in `` Hot Water,'' desperately trying to breathe life into the cliche that he has become, <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s Official Tropical Hedonist. The new LP is cruise-line predictable. He softly sings the praises of the <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> air -LRB- or, as he affectedly sings en francais, `` L'Air de la Louisiane'' -RRB- _ only a dozen years after he sang the same song about `` <LOCATION> Biloxi </LOCATION>,'' one state away. Here comes the `` Prince of Tides.'' There goes the `` King of Somewhere Hot.'' This is n't rock' n' roll; this is the Weather Channel. Musically, things are little better. There's an all-star guest list _ <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Winwood </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Neville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION>, even <PERSON> Grover </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> _ but what you hear here, mon, is the misplaced sound of steel drums. And if the pseudo-Caribbean schtick were n't wearing thin by now, `` Hot Water'' finds <PERSON> Buffett </PERSON> pretentious _ three of these songs begin with spoken soliloquies _ and mean-spirited. When he's not complaining that his songs are n't on the radio, he's bordering on misogyny: complaining that `` baby's gone shopping'' when she ought to stay home, forsaking `` bimbo limbo'' to search for a `` smart woman in a real short skirt.'' <PERSON> Buffett </PERSON>'s magic with his audience has been that they wished they could live their lives like his songs. Songs like these make it hard to remember why anyone ever felt that way. _ By <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer
