<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Star Watch: The Frank, Intense and Combative Kirk</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>' autobiography, `` The Ragman's Son,'' has spent weeks on non-fiction best-seller lists, a position generally accorded such female stars as <PERSON> Lauren </PERSON> <PERSON> Bacall </PERSON>, <PERSON> Shelley </PERSON> <PERSON> Winters </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ingrid </PERSON> <PERSON> Bergman </PERSON> How did <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> make the magic list when other actors have failed? The secret may be that his book is just as frank, intense and combative as the public's image of <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> over the past four decades. <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> has never walked away from a fight. Many a producer, director and co-star can recall scars acquired in encounters with <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON>. He turned his back on a seven-year contract from <PERSON> Hal </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallis </PERSON> at a time when most actors would grab it. He defied the industry powers by hiring the blacklisted <PERSON> Dalton </PERSON> <PERSON> Trumbo </PERSON> to write `` Spartacus.'' As revealed in `` The Ragman's Son,'' he romanced a wide range of <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>'s glamour queens, including <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON>, <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Tierney </PERSON>, <PERSON> Marlene </PERSON> <PERSON> Dietrich </PERSON>, <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Sothern </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rita </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayworth </PERSON>. <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> seems to be a man who got everything he wanted. But he had two great frustrations. He was madly in love with <PERSON> Pier </PERSON> <PERSON> Angeli </PERSON>, but despite their engagement, he could never escape her ever-present parents. He starred in `` One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest'' on Broadway but could never make a movie deal He became too old for the role, and son <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> co-produced the film, which won an Academy Award for <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Nicholson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>, a vigorous 69, recently reminisced about his life and times at the <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> offices of <PERSON> Bryna </PERSON> <PERSON> Productions </PERSON>, named for his mother. He told of the inception of his autobiography. `` I was driving to <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION> one day, and I saw a sailor hitchhiking. I had been in the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, so I picked him up. When he got in the car, he looked at me and said, ` Do you know who you are?' `` Well, I thought about that, and it's an interesting question,'' he said. The actor's search for <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> led him to <PERSON> Issur </PERSON> <PERSON> Danielovitch </PERSON>, the son of illiterate, Russian-Jewish immigrants in <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION>, N.Y. The father was a cold, distant, brawling alcoholic whose love neither Issur nor <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> could achieve. `` It's a terrible thing for a young kid who has a father who's so physically strong,'' said <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> `` You think, ` My God, I can never be that strong, I can never be that big.' My father was a rag man, yet to me he was somebody. So living with my six sisters and my mother, I had no identity. `` When my father left, I thought, ` Why am I not with my father? I'm a boy! Why am I with the women?''' Young <PERSON> Issur </PERSON> escaped the `` suffocating'' female atmosphere to attend <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lawrence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, and he never went home again, except for brief visits. He discovered acting in college, went on to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> where his looks _ like carved granite _ and intense style attracted <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> offers. And he went on his own terms. `` From the very beginning, I was always independent, a maverick,'' he remarked. `` I did n't belong to any studio. There were good things about that, but there were bad things, too. It was lonely. Everybody else belonged to studios, and they were going to singing and dancing lessons. `` There were a lot of good things to be said for the oldtime studio system that I did not belong to. They developed stars and got parts for them in movies. I was n't part of that. I was sort of outside.'' <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>' film career has been marked by an affinity for forceful heroic roles, from his part as a calculating boxer in 1949's `` Champion'' to his depiction of <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON> in 1956's `` Lust for Life. Both films earned him Academy Award nominations. In `` Spartacus,'' perhaps <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>' greatest role, he starred as the leader of slaves rebelling against Republican <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>. At the same time, <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> has shown a flair for the comic, especially as a sharp-tongued inmate in the 1970 movie `` There Was a Crooked Man.'' His first film role came in 1946's `` The Strange Love of <PERSON> Martha </PERSON> <PERSON> Ivers </PERSON>,'' and his last appearance was in the 1987 NBC production of `` Inherit the Wind.'' <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> has been known for his frankness, and he had these evaluations about some of his friends and colleagues: <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON>: `` One of the most remarkable men I ever worked with. We never got along, though we did four pictures together. Politically we were complete opposites.'' <PERSON> Burt </PERSON> <PERSON> Lancaster </PERSON>: `` I like <PERSON> Burt </PERSON>. He's quite different; for example, he's a great lover of music and opera. Most people would never expect that of <PERSON> Burt </PERSON>. If I ever need <PERSON> Burt </PERSON>, I call him; if he needs me, he calls me. It's a wonderful relationship.'' <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanwyck </PERSON> -LRB- who starred in his first film -RRB-: `` She was pretty tough with me at first. I was new, did n't know anybody, and she sort of ignored me for two weeks. But I always forgive any slights like that when I see talent and a professional attitude.'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchum </PERSON>: `` Never my kind of guy. I always kidded him about those stories he'd tell about being a hobo; they seemed to change every time he told them. But obviously he is a talented guy, and listen, he's had a tremendous career.'' <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>: `` The nicest thing I can say about <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> is what I put in a note some time ago; he told me it's the only note of mine he has kept. I said to him, ` <PERSON> Michael </PERSON>, I'm more proud of how you handle your success than I am of your success.' And I think we'll still be hearing a lot from him.'' <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>: `` <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> ... <PERSON> Issur </PERSON> <PERSON> Danielovitch </PERSON>, the ragman's son. I've taken 450 pages to try to explain who I am. And I'm not sure I know yet. `` The best way to sum it up would be in the character of <PERSON> McMurphy </PERSON> in ` One Flew over the Cuckoo's Nest,' the role I so desperately wanted to play on the screen. <PERSON> McMurphy </PERSON> tries to lift this piece of machinery and fails. They're all looking and feeling sorry for him. He turns to face them and says, ` But I tried. Dammit, I tried.'''
