<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Artists: International Applause for Opera in English</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The lights go up on `` Carmen'' to reveal an extravagantly gaudy junkyard that owes as much to `` West Side Story'' as it does to the fiery passions of composer <PERSON> Georges </PERSON> <PERSON> Bizet </PERSON>. Another night sees <PERSON> Giacomo </PERSON> <PERSON> Puccini </PERSON>'s `` Tosca'' updated to the fascist <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> of World War II and performed on a tilted stage. The two productions are the season openers at the English National Opera, a company that is making an international name for itself not only on the strength of its singing but for its imaginative stagings. Launched by <PERSON> Lilian </PERSON> <PERSON> Baylis </PERSON> as the <PERSON> Sadler </PERSON>'s Wells Opera in 1931, the company moved to its present home, the 2,358-seat <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> Coliseum, in 1968. It changed its name to the English National Opera in 1974, and has since gathered a burgeoning reputation for productions that prize the work over individual stars, and artistic vision over vanity vehicles. `` We are a theater and not a museum,'' music director <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Elder </PERSON> said in an interview. `` Theater needs to be exploratory, renewing, inquisitive. ... It's not just a matter of doing the old classics in a sensationalistic way.'' Indeed not. For although the <ORGANIZATION> ENO </ORGANIZATION> has launched its 21st season at the Coliseum with two warhorses, `` Tosca'' and `` Carmen,'' the breadth of its repertory also includes Broadway musicals, <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sondheim </PERSON>'s `` Pacific Overtures'' and commissioned British works, such as <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Blake </PERSON>'s `` The Plumber's Gift.'' Nov. 9 sees the European premiere of <ORGANIZATION> Philip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Glass </ORGANIZATION>' `` The Making of the Representative for Planet 8,'' the American composer's first work at the ENO since `` Akhnaten'' in 1985. In December, <PERSON> ENO </PERSON> mounts the first professional British staging of <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> Rimsky-Korsakov </PERSON>'s 1895 `` Christmas Eve. In January, the <ORGANIZATION> ENO </ORGANIZATION> will have the British debut of <PERSON> Aribert </PERSON> <PERSON> Reimann </PERSON>'s `` Lear,'' based on the Shakespeare tragedy. It's the same eclectic mix of the tested and the untried that has wrought what <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Kenyon </PERSON> in <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> called `` a revolution in the standard of theater being offered to opera-goers.'' `` I take for granted that ENO is the reference point of adventurous, living music theater,'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Jonas </PERSON>, the company's artistic director. `` Opera took a long time to be accepted as essential in British life. ... We've done a certain amount to help that.'' The ENO is responsible for 46 percent of the annual operatic activity in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. During its 10-month 1988-89 season, the company will present 204 performances of 18 operas in what <PERSON> Jonas </PERSON> calls `` one of the heaviest repertory systems in the world.'' Production costs range from $ 33,500 to $ 295,000. The upper figure is about half the cost of the most expensive productions at the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opera </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, Covent Garden, the <ORGANIZATION> ENO </ORGANIZATION>'s principal <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> rival. In 1984, the company toured five <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> cities, winning raves from <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> with works ranging from <PERSON> Giuseppe </PERSON> <PERSON> Verdi </PERSON>'s 1851 `` Rigoletto,'' transplanted to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> a century later, to <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Britten </PERSON>'s patriotic 1953 `` Gloriana. The company's white-tie-and-tails version of `` The Mikado'' was to be broadcast by PBS in late October. In spring 1990, plans are in the works to perform a Czech opera and <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Weill </PERSON>'s 1949 `` Street Scene'' in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Wherever the ENO appears, one constant remains: It presents all foreign-language operas in English translations, whether it's Prokofiev or <LOCATION> Puccini </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Mozart </PERSON> or <PERSON> Massenet </PERSON> `` What is missing is the texture of the original language,'' said British soprano <PERSON> Josephine </PERSON> <PERSON> Barstow </PERSON>. But <LOCATION> Barstow </LOCATION> understands the policy, even if she did n't always agree with it: `` The fact that the ENO always does perform in English is one reason why the audience has such a high level of concentration. Nowhere in the world have I personally encountered such concentration. Audiences come to listen and to think.'' She said it proved useful to performers, too. `` It's an enormous advantage to young singers to sing a major role like Salome in their own language,'' said <LOCATION> Barstow </LOCATION>, who first sang <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON>' vengeful heroine for the <ORGANIZATION> ENO </ORGANIZATION> in 1975. `` It's quite easy to learn opera in a language you speak reasonably well. Familiar works fuel the debate. A new production of <PERSON> Verdi </PERSON>'s `` La Traviata'' won mixed reviews both for peculiarities of its staging and lapses in translation. But earlier stagings in English of <PERSON> Dmitri </PERSON> <PERSON> Shostakovich </PERSON>'s lesser-known `` Lady Macbeth of <LOCATION> Mtsensk </LOCATION>'' and <PERSON> Leos </PERSON> <PERSON> Janacek </PERSON>'s `` The Makropolous Case,'' both starring <LOCATION> Barstow </LOCATION>, helped secure those operas' exalted positions within the world repertory In November, <LOCATION> Barstow </LOCATION> travels to the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Opera </LOCATION> to sing `` Lady Macbeth'' for the first time in Russian, which she might never have done had she not attempted it first in English. `` I've tried out a lot of roles with the ENO before I've done them elsewhere,'' said <LOCATION> Barstow </LOCATION>. She is one of several singers who has reached international status through the ENO. Others include <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, <PERSON> Felicity </PERSON> <PERSON> Lott </PERSON> and <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Allan </PERSON>. In September, she appeared as a soloist in <PERSON> Beethoven </PERSON>'s Ninth Symphony under the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Symphony </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orchestra </ORGANIZATION>. In 1989-90, she is scheduled to sing the Marschallin in <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON>' `` Der Rosenkavalier'' at the <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> Grand Opera. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Jonas </PERSON> is pleased that alumni-turned-stars more often than not return to their roots: `` You do pinch yourself and think, ` Oh he's lost to us.' But quite a few come back in very favorable positions.'' `` I suppose I'm one of the most loyal ones, if you like,'' said <LOCATION> Barstow </LOCATION>, who acknowledges the ENO as home base. `` It's comforting to feel you belong somewhere in the whole big world of opera.''
