<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Books and Authors: Striving for Perfection Is Not Perfectly Normal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENEVA COLLINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> makes $ 250,000 a year working for <PERSON> E.F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON> and prides herself on being `` a shark.'' <PERSON> Anita </PERSON> runs miles every day but has been bulimic for eight years. <PERSON> Marjorie </PERSON> has made straight A's all her life but panics and overprepares for every test. What all these women have in common, says <PERSON> Colette </PERSON> <PERSON> Dowling </PERSON>, is an overwhelming desire to achieve perfection. In her book `` Perfect Women'' -LRB- Summit, $ 18.95 -RRB-, <PERSON> Dowling </PERSON> argues that this striving for ever-higher goals _ hours of aerobics every day, 60-hour work weeks, making every meal from scratch _ is not a healthy exercise to fulfill one's potential but a desperate scramble to fill an inner void. `` An artistic drive is satisfying. A drive to perform is not. ... It's a kind of rigid, compulsive _ kind of a symptom, as compared to something that's really joyful and self-expressive and gives back to us,'' the author said. <PERSON> Dowling </PERSON>, best known for her 1981 best seller `` The Cinderella Complex,'' recently talked about her new book in an interview at her publisher's office. `` The whole drive to be perfect comes out of a feeling of inferiority,'' she said. `` We would n't even be interested in the idea of perfection if there was n't something that we psychologically were compensating for.'' Asked why she thinks this striving for perfection is unique to women, <PERSON> Dowling </PERSON> said, `` Women as an entire gender have been disparaged culturally for eons, and it's a particular kind of gender feeling about self that gets handed down from the mother to the daughter. `` And now that there's so much opportunity available to women, I think we've just stepped into a new kind of performance arena. I think we're using our achievements to bolster our self-esteem, in the way we used to use our appearance or our cooking or our housekeeping skills or whatever.'' She cites a litany of symptoms from which these overachievers suffer: anorexia and bulimia; drug and alcohol problems; compulsive shopping. All except the drug and alcohol abuse are overwhelmingly female problems. The premise of the `` Cinderella Complex'' was that women had a deep-seated belief that they could not take care of themselves, that despite the gains of the women's movement they were still waiting for a Prince Charming to whisk them off to happily ever after. <PERSON> Dowling </PERSON>, 50, said that work was based on her own experience. In the 1970s, after ending a 9-year-marriage to an alcoholic, she moved in with a man she still lives with in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Hudson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>. There, <PERSON> Dowling </PERSON>, who had supported herself and her three children as a free-lance writer, abandoned her career and became a full-time housewife. Her partner's refusal to accept her dependency, as well as the therapy she was undergoing, gave her the initiative to write `` The Cinderella Complex.'' `` Perfect Women'' is similarly based on <PERSON> Dowling </PERSON>'s personal experience. The author found that despite the success of `` The Cinderella Complex'' -LRB- 26 weeks on the best-seller list -RRB- she still felt insecure about her work and at a loss for her next project. At the same time, her eldest daughter, <PERSON> Gabrielle </PERSON>, a star scholar, athlete and beauty, dropped out of <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and revealed that she had been bulimic for years. <PERSON> Dowling </PERSON> realized that her own relentless drive for success _ so she could like herself _ had been passed down to her daughter. In `` Perfect Women,'' Dowling cites psychological studies detailing the mother-daughter relationship that starts at the crib. `` They -LRB- mothers -RRB- are not overly involved with us -LRB- daughters -RRB- as separate persons; they're overly involved with us as extensions of themselves,'' <PERSON> Dowling </PERSON> said. `` This sticky kind of bonding is very unique to the mother-daughter relationship. This is not to say boys do n't have their own problems, because God knows they do, but this is something very specific to the gender.'' The way for a woman to get off the perfection treadmill, she said, is to psychologically separate herself from her mother, which can be done through therapy, self-exploration, perhaps confrontation. `` Perfect Women'' suffers from the kind of generalized prescription that most self-help books offer, but if it makes a few self-improvement junkies stop buying these kinds of pop psychology books and learn to accept themselves as they are, then it's done its work.
</TEXT>
