<NOTE>For release Thursday, Oct. 20, and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Japanese Doctors Shy From Giving Cancer Patients Details</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI YAMAGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Almost 200,000 Japanese died last year of cancer, most without knowing they had it _ unless they figured it out themselves. Their doctors had n't told them the truth. Traditionally, the Japanese have been unlikely to question the authority of the medical profession, but that appears to be changing as a well-educated people want to know more about what ails them. And doctors are thinking about revising their ethics, which have been based on the belief that patients are depressed if told they have cancer, and will die happier if they do n't know. `` I guess about 90 percent of the doctors still do n't tell,'' said <PERSON> Toshio </PERSON> <PERSON> Takahashi </PERSON>, professor of surgery at <ORGANIZATION> Kyoto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prefectural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION>. But to <PERSON> Jinro </PERSON> <PERSON> Itami </PERSON>, cancer specialist at <ORGANIZATION> Shibata </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Okayama </LOCATION>, the real issue is not the propriety of informing patients but how to reduce their fear of death and increase their `` fighting spirit.'' <LOCATION> Itami </LOCATION> four years ago founded a patient-support program called Meaningful Life Therapy. Seven of his patients attempted a morale-building climb of <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Blanc </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> last summer, and three of them reached the summit. `` The earlier patients know about their condition, the better off they are,'' he said, adding that witholding information can create fear and sorrow and delay recovery. The debate, of course, is not limited to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. Soviet doctors generally avoid telling a patient directly, according to Dr. <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> Napalkov </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S.S.R. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oncological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>. In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, doctors tend toward disclosure, said Dr. <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Itami </PERSON> said it is almost impossible to keep patients ignorant as they hear about the disease and its treatments everywhere. But even he says that unless patients are ready for the worst, telling them will only cause depression. Instead, he guides them to want to know about their illness and its treatment. `` It is very important for patients to know about their own lives and their condition,'' he said. The public seems to agree. About 60 percent want doctors to tell them even if there is no hope of recovery, according to a poll of 5,608 adults a year ago by the <ORGANIZATION> Mainichi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shimbun </ORGANIZATION>, a Japanese national daily. If the disease is likely to be cured, 78 percent want to know. A separate poll of 500 doctors showed 76 percent would not tell the patient if the condition is hopeless. `` It should be us patients, not doctors, that decide how to live the days left in front of us,'' said <PERSON> Haruyo </PERSON> <PERSON> Inouye </PERSON>, a 37-year-old free-lance writer who had a breast cancer operation in April. `` Doctors should tell us so that we do n't have to waste time being scared because of ignorance.'' She complained that her doctor had not told her the side effect of a hormonal medicine she took after surgery. She was shocked when her menstruation became irregular, thinking something else was wrong with her. <PERSON> Toshiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Murase </PERSON>, pediatrician and executive member of the <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>'s board of trustees, said it's important to respect the patient's right to know but satisfying the right to know is a different story. `` Some patients might be able to end their lives happier without knowing everything,'' he said, adding that Japanese doctors' most important task is to help reduce their patients' physical pain. There never has been a court ruling in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> over the issue of a patient's right to know, said lawyer <PERSON> Katsuji </PERSON> <PERSON> Hotta </PERSON>, who recently was named to a committee to examine the issue for <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. The association has decided to investigate medical, moral and legal aspects of medical treatment, and appointed 10 people from various professions to talk about `` explanation and consent.'' The group includes novelist <PERSON> Ayako </PERSON> <PERSON> Sono </PERSON>; the president of the <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Eiji </PERSON> <PERSON> Suzuki </PERSON>; philosopher <PERSON> Yujiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Nakamura </PERSON> and professors of medicine. Cancer is <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s No. 1 killer disease, causing 26.6 percent of all deaths last year, with stomach cancer topping the list.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Oct. 20</NOTE>
