<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--ColdLaboratory 1stLd-Writethru Adv20 10-17 0693</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Cold Laboratory, 1st Ld-Writethru, Adv 20, b0965,0709</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Thursday, Oct. 20, and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Scientists Seek Physics Answers at Cornell Cold Spot</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Restores dropped word `temperature' in 2nd graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM KATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ITHACA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 There are no dangling icicles in <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>, no frost on the walls, and breathing does n't produce vapor clouds. But it's still one of the coldest known spots in the universe. `` It does n't look very impressive but we are going to go a million times colder than the coldest natural place we know of,'' says <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON>, head of the low-temperature physics group at <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Microkelvin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON> and his colleagues, using a $ 1.5 million super-refrigeration unit, will try to achieve absolute zero _ the temperature at which even atoms stop rubbing together and creating heat. `` We think we can take it down to between 1 and 10 microkelvin,'' he said. `` And each step of the way, we could be finding new effects.'' The only other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> deep-freeze laboratory is under construction at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION>. Labs in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> have hit 12 microkelvin. How cold is that? The temperature of deep space, minus 270 degrees Fahrenheit, is only 3 on the <PERSON> Kelvin </PERSON> scale, which uses absolute zero for a reference point. Absolute zero in Fahrenheit is minus 459 degrees, while room temperature would be 293 <PERSON> Kelvin </PERSON>. A millikelvin is a thousandth of a <PERSON> Kelvin </PERSON>, so a microkelvin is a millionth. Dropping from 12 microkelvin to 10 microkelvin might seem inconsequential, but <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON> adds this perspective: `` If you increased room temperature by the same ratio, everything would melt or disintegrate.'' The researchers are n't simply out to break records, though. `` The importance of this type of research lies in realizing the strange things that happen at low temperatures,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Oosterhuis </PERSON>, section head of the condensed matter sciences unit at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>. `` One just never knows what's going to happen This research provides us with a probe into an area where we've never been before.'' Among the strange discoveries of extremely low-temperature research has been superconductivity _ electricity with no loss to resistance _ at 4 <PERSON> Kelvin </PERSON>. `` Sometimes it is the arithmetic or the theory behind the research that has the practical application,'' said <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Liebenberg </PERSON>, who helped the lab get <ORGANIZATION> NSF </ORGANIZATION> funding before he left in April for the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION>. `` Sometimes the technology produced has broader applications in other fields. The most important aspect, though, is that these facilities will be breeding grounds of technological spinoffs for future low temperature research,'' <PERSON> Liebenberg </PERSON> said. Individual scientists have conducted low temperature research before, but the lack of a permanent facility to maintain such temperatures indefinitely and allow for varied experiments has been an obstacle, <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON> said. `` Now we have an adequate tool to find _ or at least search properly _ for the answers to all the open questions that remain in front of us.'' The rooms adjoining <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION>'s 2,800-square-foot underground laboratory are designed to eliminate all stray heat, including that produced from the most minute vibrations and from radio-frequency electrical signals. To that end, they are lined with butcher block wood and galvanized electromagnetic shielding and have specially grounded electrical wiring and incandescent lighting. The low temperature instruments are secured by concrete sewer pipes filled with sand. The supercooling machines themselves are rigid aluminum, filled with liquid helium, copper and superconducting magnets. The apparatus stands 12 feet tall and weighs about 700 pounds, but the focus is on a 36-inch vacuum cylinder. To reach microkelvin temperatures, a process that takes about two weeks, scientists first polarize copper with a superconducting magnet, then cool it to around 10 millikelvin in the refrigerator, which uses liquid helium rather than freon gas for cooling. Once the copper is at 10 millikelvin, the magnetic field is reduced and the copper nuclei, which are now aligned and highly ordered, take over, further cooling everything in the surrounding medium. `` We can never be sure what will be found,'' said <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON>. `` Maybe we'll have the good fortune to stumble upon a new science.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Oct. 20</NOTE>
