<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Food costs, showing further effects from the drought, accelerated sharply in September, but a big drop in energy costs kept the overall rise in wholesale prices at a moderate 0.4 percent, the government reported. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration claimed that Friday's report showed inflation was not heating up. But some private economists expressed worries about what could happen if world oil prices suddenly rebound. The September increase represented a drop from an August increase of 0.6 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Retail sales in September dropped for the second consecutive month, the government said, confirming economists' views that the confidence of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> consumers is slipping. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Friday that sales fell 0.4 percent last month to a seasonally adjusted $ 133.7 billion. That followed a dip of 0.1 percent in August and was the first back-to-back drop since September-October 1987. The government data is consistent with a survey earlier this week for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, a business research organization.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industrial production in September failed to rise for the first time in seven months, the government said, suggesting to economists that the overheated manufacturing sector is cooling a bit. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said Friday that output at the nation's facories, mines and utilities was unchanged last month after increasing a slight 0.2 percent in August and an unusually large 1.2 percent in July. The production index has gone 12 months without a decline, but September was the first time since February that it did not rise.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal regulators pledged $ 1.3 billion to rescue 11 insolvent savings institutions in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, selling them to a cable television company. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said Friday that <ORGANIZATION> Adam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> @ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bryant </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, a cable TV station operator, is investing $ 65 million now and an additional $ 15 million by the end of 1990 to acquire the 11 institutions. They are being merged under the name of <ORGANIZATION> Olney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. All deposits, even those over the insurance limit of $ 100,000, are transferring, the bank board said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s profit rose 3.2 percent in the third quarter, the world's largest computer maker said in a report that lifted its stock. Revenue climbed 5.3 percent, an indication that <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> is succeeding in switching customers to new large and mid-sized computers without a big drop in sales of older models, analysts said Friday. `` They -LRB- earnings -RRB- were pretty decent,'' said <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, an analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Soundview </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Stamford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Allegheny </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said it still intends to emerge from Chapter 11 reorganization by year's end or early in 1989 even though the parties in the case have asked for a month's delay in a key hearing. `` It's very common for large claims to be made, but they are ultimately settled for significantly less,'' company spokesman <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Romanoff </PERSON> said Friday. Earlier, company officials told Bankruptcy Judge <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Cosetti </PERSON> that they need time to study $ 2.5 billion in claims pending against the consumer products company.
