 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> signed into law a bill aimed at spurring the manufacture of vehicles that can run on fuels other than gasoline. `` This bill is a landmark in the quest for alternative forms of energy,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said Friday. The legislation has been billed by its supporters as providing a means of lowering <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dependence on foreign oil, cutting pollution and curbing the nation's trade deficit.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Miami News, an afternoon newspaper that has won five Pulitzer prizes, will be closed by the end of the year if no buyer can be found, parent <ORGANIZATION> Cox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION> said. The staff of The News, which was founded in 1896, was informed of the decision Friday. <ORGANIZATION> Cox </ORGANIZATION> officials said The News was losing too much money. The newspaper has operated since 1966 under a joint operating agreement with The <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION>, owned by <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Japanese yen is strong and the dollar is weak, and salmon fanciers in the Northwest are paying for this lesson in international economics at the fish counter. `` It's outrageous,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> of Pure Food Fish in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>'s Pike Place Market. Fresh chinook, or king, salmon steaks and filets that sold a year ago for $ 4.95 and $ 5.95 a pound now run $ 7.95 to $ 8.95, <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> said Friday. The bad news for consumers has been good news for Northwest fishermen, who have been netting many more dollars for the same amount of work.
