<FIRST>r f PM-Poll-Economy     10-17 0685</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poll-Economy,0705</SECOND>
<HEAD>Americans See Economy As Stable, But Not The Market</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Americans are confident of a stable national economy and improving personal finances the next few years, but they remain wary of <LOCATION> Wall </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General-Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> poll has found. A year after the stock market crashed, 71 percent of the 1,125 adults in the national survey said they regard it as a risky place to invest, and fully a third saw a good chance it will plummet again in the next year or two. But three-quarters said the crash had little or no effect on their lives, and only one in 10 said their finances had worsened in the past year. Even among the wealthiest, seven in 10 felt little impact from the crash. There was one apparent residual impact from the market's crash: More than six in 10 in the survey said they were being more cautious with their money now than they were a year ago. The Dow Jones industrial average dived 508 points on Oct. 19, 1987, after dropping 108 points the previous Friday. Stock losses amounted to $ 500 billion, but the crash did not spark a recession, as had been feared. In the poll, 25 percent expected the nation's economy to worsen in the next few years. But nearly as many said it would improve, and a 43 percent plurality said they expected little change in the economy. There was even greater optimism about personal gains. Fifty-five percent expected their family's economic situation to improve in the short term, a third expected to hold steady and only 6 percent expected to do worse. The survey found a receptive audience for Republican presidential nominee <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s theme of national prosperity. Most expressed satisfaction with their family's income, with 57 percent saying they were `` doing all right'' and 9 percent rating themselves `` well off.'' Nonetheless, a considerable 29 percent said they were `` just getting by'' and 5 percent said they were `` in hard times'' financially. The true number likely is higher because telephone surveys exclude the poorest households, the 7 percent without phones. A third in the poll said their family finances were better off now compared to a year ago, and a 56 percent majority said their situation was the same. Just 12 percent said they were doing worse. Seventy-three percent overall said they were saving for the future. But the market was not a preferred choice for saving: Seventy percent said they had no money in stocks, and 71 percent saw the market as risky. Among the wealthiest Americans, those making $ 50,000 or more a year, more than half had money in the market. But even in this group, 71 percent said they regarded the stock market as a risky investment. Even though three in 10 overall had stock investments, only 6 percent said the crash had a major impact on their lives, and only 15 percent said it had a moderate impact, for a total of 21 percent. By contrast, 28 percent said the market crash had little impact on their lives and 47 percent said it had no impact at all _ a total of 75 percent. Even among the wealthiest, 69 percent felt little or no impact. On the outlook for the market, 33 percent said there was a good chance of another crash in the next year or two and 26 percent were unsure. The plurality, 41 percent, said another crash was `` not too likely'' soon. The poll did not find broad support for greater government regulation of Wall Street. While a quarter favored it, four in 10 said current oversight was sufficient and 9 percent wanted less regulation. The rest were unsure. The poll, conducted Sept. 6-14, had a margin of error of plus or minus three percentage points. <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a communications company based in <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, publishes the Richmond Times-Dispatch, the Richmond News Leader, the <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION> -RRB- <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> Winston-Salem </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION> -RRB- Journal, and operates TV stations <ORGANIZATION> WXFL </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, WCBD in <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> WJKS </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
