<FIRST>r f PM-GoingPublic 1stLd-Writethru f0007 10-17 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Going Public, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0007,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>IPOs Grind To Halt in Wake of Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs, Of the ..., with one graf to CORRECT to
Thornton sted Thorton. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, ``The number ...</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: For Release 10 a.m. EDT; time set by source</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Last year's stock market crash decimated the hopes of nearly half the companies waiting to go public and reduced the amount of cash others could raise in the equity market, a study released today said. Of the 229 businesses on file with the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Oct. 19, 1987 to issue stock for the first time, 45 percent had abandoned those plans nine months after `` Black Monday,'' according to the accounting and consulting firm <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornton </PERSON>. `` The number of busted -LRB- initial public offerings -RRB- we identified is unprecedented,'' said <PERSON> Chet </PERSON> <PERSON> Borgida </PERSON>, director of the firm's capital markets group and head of the study `` We all knew that going public was tougher after Black Monday. We just did n't know how tough.'' Fewer than 25 percent of the companies planning to go public were able to do so since the crash, the study showed. Another 31 percent still were on file with the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> to go public as of July 31. Those companies that braved the equities market succeeded in raising an average $ 15.9 million. But <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornton </PERSON> estimated that each of those same companies would have raised an average of $ 7.2 million more had they completed their public offerings before the crash. Small and mid-sized companies were most severely affected, <PERSON> Borgida </PERSON> said. `` Most of the companies that wanted to go public could n't, and those that did had to settle for less capital than they needed.'' Of 51 companies that participated in a Grant <PERSON> Thornton </PERSON> poll, 27 said they had obtained financing from alternative sources including commercial banks, private placements and, less frequently, from venture capitalists. Despite the grim environment, 86 percent of the companies participating in the poll _ including half of the businesses that withdrew their initial public offerings _ said they would considering going public if they could make the choice again. `` As least in the view of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s entrepreneurs, there is no substitute for going public,'' <PERSON> Borgida </PERSON> said. `` Even in this most difficult year for financing, companies still believe that they can raise the greatest amount of capital most efficiently through the public equity markets.''
</TEXT>
