<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Grain and soybean futures were mostly lower in early trading today on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>, reflecting pessimism about grain sales to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and an increase in crop sales by farmers. But early losses were slight due to the supportive influence of weekend rains in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> and relatively dry growing conditions in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, which are large producers of soybeans, analysts said. `` Their situation is improving down there, but they still need rain,'' said <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Lespinasse </PERSON>, a trader in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> with <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The weekend rain in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> slowed the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn and soybean harvest, which is more than half complete, <PERSON> Lespinasse </PERSON> said. More rain was expected today and Wednesday. On Friday, negotiators for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> ended two days of talks in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> without a new long-term grain agreement. Disappointment over the failure to produce an agreement continued to weigh on the markets today, <PERSON> Lespinasse </PERSON> said. In early trading, wheat was -LCB- cent to 2 -RCB- cents lower with December at $ 4.26 a bushel; corn was unchanged to 1 \ cents lower with December at $ 2.93 a bushel; oats were 2 -LCB- cents lower across the board with December at $ 2.50 a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent to 3 -LCB- cents lower with November at $ 8.02 a bushel Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were mostly lower in early trading on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Live cattle were .18 cent lower to .05 cent higher with October at 72.85 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .17 cent lower to .18 cent higher with October at 82.05 cents a pound; hogs were unchanged to .30 cent lower with October at 40.25 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .02 cent to .30 cent lower with February at 48.80 cents a pound. Cattle finished mostly lower on Friday while pork futures were mixed.
