<TEXT>
 Stock prices were little changed in quiet trading today, getting little benefit from new evidence of a slowing economy. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials slipped .89 to 2,132.29 by noontime on Wall Street. Gainers slightly outnumbered losers in nationwide trading of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> Exchange-listed issues, with 610 up, 600 down and 563 unchanged. Analysts said traders took a generally upbeat view of the current state of the economy, believing that growth hasasonable basis.'' Lawyers for the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> had contested <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>'s motion to remove <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON>. `` I think the judge's opinion was in accordance with our legal position,'' said <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldsmith </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> deputy litigation counsel who is handling the day-to-day affairs of the <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> case. `` Right now we're looking forward to getting on with the merits of the case.'' Attorneys for others who have sued <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON> also applauded the ruling of <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON>, who is widely known as a no-nonsense judge who often rules in the government's favor in white-collar fraud cases. `` I am delighted by the decision,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Berger </PERSON>, a lead attorney for shareholders that have filed a class action suit against <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>. He described the defense effort to disqualify <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON> as `` just a litigation ploy, an attempt to stall the evil day.'' <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Anreder </PERSON> said in a statement: `` Our attorneys had a professional obligation to bring this issue before the court. Since it is their considered view that, based on the facts in the motion, Judge <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON>'s position is incorrect, the matter will be placed before the 2nd circuit Court of Appeals.'' The <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> filed a civil suit against <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>, its high-yield bond financier <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> and three other employees of the firm Sept. 7, alleging they schemed with <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON> to profit on insider trading, manipulate stock, cheat <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> clients and commit other frauds. The defendants denied the allegations. Up to now the case has largely been stalled over disputes about <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON>'s impartiality and pretrial evidence requests by both sides.
