<HEAD>Court Refuses To Block Vaccine Lawsuit in Virginia Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A $ 10 million lawsuit against the maker of a whooping cough vaccine that allegedly caused brain damage in an infant should go to trial, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled Monday. The court, without comment, let stand a ruling in a <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> case that federal law does not foreclose such suits under state regulations that protect consumers against defectively designed products, even if the federal government approves the products. In other business-related cases, the justices: _ Refused to hear an appeal by <ORGANIZATION> Hallmark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of an injunction barring it from selling greeting cards resembling those produced by <ORGANIZATION> Blue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mountain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION>, a small company in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> _ Agreed to consider allowing states to give larger retirement benefits to public employees forced to quit work before age 60 The case involves an <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> pension law provision that gave a 61-year-old state employee lower disability retirement benefits than she would have gotten if she had been younger. _ Agreed to hear a <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration appeal aimed at making it easier for the government to conduct tax-fraud investigations The justices said they will use a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> case involving the <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scientology </ORGANIZATION> to settle a dispute over the power of the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> to obtain and use confidential documents. The vaccine case involves <PERSON> Tracy </PERSON> <PERSON> Abbot </PERSON>, who was 5 months old in August 1983 when she was inoculated with a vaccine called Tri-Immunol manufactured by <ORGANIZATION> Lederle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION>, a division of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cyanamid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. Her mother sued <ORGANIZATION> Lederle </ORGANIZATION> in 1986 charging the vaccine caused brain damage in Tracy and asking $ 10 million in damages. Tri-Immunol is a vaccine against diphtheria, tetanus and whooping cough _ or pertussis _ and is administered to millions of children without serious side effects. But it has caused serious injury in a small number of children. The vaccine is approved by the <ORGANIZATION> federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> and other government health agencies. Only one other company in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is licensed to produce a whooping cough vaccine. Whooping cough claimed thousands of lives before the vaccine was developed. The most serious <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> epidemic was in 1934 when there were 265,000 reported cases and 7,500 deaths. The Abbot suit contends Tri-Immunol is `` unreasonably dangerous'' and says <ORGANIZATION> Lederle </ORGANIZATION> failed to develop a safer vaccine even though other forms of the vaccine have been used outside the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. A federal judge threw out the suit, but the 4th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> reinstated it in April. The appeals court rejected arguments that the federal government's interest in promoting use of the vaccine would be frustrated by permitting suits alleging violation of state regulations. Federal law does not pre-empt such suits, the appeals court said. In a somewhat related issue, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled in June that the government may be forced to pay damages when a vaccine it licenses causes the disease it was intended to prevent. That case reinstated a suit in behalf of a boy who contracted polio after receiving a dose of federally approved vaccine. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has not announced a position on the Abbot suit. But the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has pointed out that alternative vaccines to the type <ORGANIZATION> Lederle </ORGANIZATION> produces have not been proven safe and effective. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has passed a law, which took full effect Oct. 1, creating a fund to help compensate children injured by vaccines. The new law places a tax on some vaccines to provide funds for injuries that occur from vaccinations after 1986.
