<FIRST>r f BC-UN-WorldDebt     10-17 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-UN-World Debt,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Says Governments, Private Banks Must Slash Debt Of Third
World</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Governments and private lenders must write off part of the Third World's debt if they hope to see those nations recover from economic stagnation, Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said in a report released Monday. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> is scheduled Wednesday to address the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> committee dealing with the world debt crisis, and the committee's resolution will go to the floor of the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> for debate In introducing the secretary-general's report, <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Ripert </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION>'s office of Development and <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cooperation </ORGANIZATION>, said that `` the service of their debt is killing investment in these -LRB- developing -RRB- countries.'' `` The report before you relates the debt problem squarely to the current crisis of development in a large part of the world,'' <PERSON> Ripert </PERSON> said. `` Lack of finance, low commodity prices, high interest rates, severe protectionism are leading to substantive net transfer of resources from developing and debtor nations to the developed countries. `` If the present trends continue, the debt crisis will remain an obstacle to growth in the indebted countries for at least another decade.'' Writing off debt, unthinkable in the financial community a year ago, `` is no more a taboo'' since the seven major industrial democracies advocated forgiving part of <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s debt at their summit in <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> last summer, according to the report. The secretary-general's report notes the so-called `` moral hazard'' of forgiving debts if that leads to new borrowing, but notes that `` politicians are not generally considered successful by their constituents if they need an international rescue.'' If the 15 most indebted developing countries received forgiveness of 30 percent of their private bank debt or interest payments due, about $ 10 billion would be available for growth-producing investment, the report says. Those 15 countries are <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>, which together owe about $ 300 billion to commercial banks. Developing nations owed a total of about $ 1.2 trillion to governments and commercial lenders at the end of 1987. Much of the new investment `` could be expected to be channelled into imports of capital goods from developed market-economy countries,'' benefiting their economies, says the report. The report estimates that those orders would boost the economies of the developed countries by about 1 percent of their industrial output. Governments in developed countries should also forgive debt owed to them as a result of foreign aid loans, the report says. The secretary-general's report was prepared with analysis by the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> on Trade and Development in consultation with leading financiers.
</TEXT>
