<HEAD>German Banks Sign Soviet Credit Pact</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A consortium of West German banks on Monday signed a $ 1.6 billion credit agreement for the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Deutsche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s largest commercial bank which is heading the consortium, said it signed the agreement with <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION>. The bank in May announced it was heading an effort to extend the credit to the Soviets to boost their consumer goods production and delivery systems. The $ 1.6 billion credit line is set up to finance West German exports aimed at expansion and modernization of the Soviet consumer goods industry, notably the food, leather, textile and clothing sectors. The agreement will be finalized with another signing ceremony scheduled for Oct. 24 in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, when Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> arrives in the Soviet capital for an official visit. Separately, the <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> German </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said it was encouring German companies to seek more joint ventures with Soviet enterprises as a means of boosting economic relations. Trade between <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> dropped to $ 8.3 billion in 1987 from $ 10.30 billion in 1986, but the <ORGANIZATION> Economics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said total trade volume is expected to stabilize this year.
