<FIRST>r f AM-SoftwareFight     10-17 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Software Fight,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>AT&amp;T May Gain Support Tuesday In Contest Over Software</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hopes appeared to fade on Monday for an agreement to end a computer industry split over the future of Unix, a base layer of software that makes it easier for different brands of computers to communicate. The fight over Unix has dismayed computer users, who are left undecided about which rival version of Unix they should adopt as their own. Programs that work with one version of Unix may not work with the other. Several companies involved in the high-stakes tussle are planning to issue a statement Tuesday rallying around <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s version of Unix, the weekly trade newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Computerworld </ORGANIZATION> said in Monday's editions. Such a group would be a rival to the <ORGANIZATION> Open </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Software </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, which includes such giants as <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Digital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equipment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Hewlett-Packard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. Although <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T invented Unix, members of the <ORGANIZATION> Open </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Software </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> say its development should be controlled by an industrywide organization so <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T does not have an unfair advantage with it. <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> T </ORGANIZATION> has said it will not join the <ORGANIZATION> Open </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Software </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> unless it uses <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T's version of Unix as the core of a new operating system. But the foundation is sticking with plans to use <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> software as the core. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Kavner </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> T </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, told <ORGANIZATION> Computerworld </ORGANIZATION> that <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T and 10 other companies will form a group to develop jointly future versions of Unix. <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T spokesman <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Muldoon </PERSON> confirmed the accuracy of the article, although he said <PERSON> Kavner </PERSON> has denied that the new group is intended to counter the influence of the rival <ORGANIZATION> Open </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Software </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Kavner </PERSON> would not identify the companies that would belong to the new Unix group, but said candidates would include <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> NCR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Amdahl </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, Ing. <ORGANIZATION> C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Olivetti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co.. SpA, <ORGANIZATION> Sun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Microsystems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Fujitsu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and others <ORGANIZATION> NCR </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> <PERSON> Kramer </PERSON> said there were tentative plans for some kind of joint statement by several companies on Tuesday. He said he did not know what it might say.
