<HEAD>Upjohn's Profit Up 20 Percent in Third Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KALAMAZOO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Upjohn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> reported a 20 percent rise in its third-quarter profit from a year earlier, due largely to an increase in foreign sales and favorable foreign-exchange rates. The pharmaceutical company said Monday that its net income in the three months ended Sept. 30 rose to $ 89.6 million, or 49 cents a share, from $ 74.6 million, or 40 cents a share, a year earlier. Third-quarter sales were up 7 percent, to $ 651.8 million from $ 608.5 million. Foreign sales, which account for 39 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Upjohn </ORGANIZATION>'s total sales, jumped 14 percent in the quarter while <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sales rose only 3 percent. The continued slide in the dollar against other major currencies made <ORGANIZATION> Upjohn </ORGANIZATION>'s products cheaper and more competitive overseas. <ORGANIZATION> Upjohn </ORGANIZATION> said its Rogaine anti-baldness formula led its major products in foreign sales growth. Rogaine was approved Aug. 17 for marketing in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and is expected to contribute to continued foreign and domestic gains, Chairman <PERSON> Theodore </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> said. Rogaine now is sold in more than 50 countries including <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, where it is called Regaine. `` But the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> approval was critical to realizing the product's full potential,'' <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Upjohn </ORGANIZATION> announced last week that Rogaine was available in pharmacies for men whose doctors prescribe it. The company said it was briefing physicians on the product in preparation for a public promotional campaign. <ORGANIZATION> Upjohn </ORGANIZATION> also reported third-quarter sales gains for its Xanax and Halcion central nervous system agents and its Micronase oral antidiabetes medication. A 19 percent increase in sales of agricultural items, including animal health products and seed, also helped sales, the company said. In the first nine months of the year, net income rose 17 percent _ to $ 272.8 million, or $ 1.47 a share, from $ 234.1 million, or $ 1.25 a share, a year earlier. Nine-month sales grew 9 percent, to $ 2.04 billion from $ 1.87 billion.
