<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     10-17 0138</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing,0148</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stock prices struggled to a small gain in quiet trading today, aided by new evidence of a slowing economy. Analysts said traders took a generally upbeat view of the current state of the economy, believing that growth has slowed of late to a steady, sustainable pace. Those hopes drew some fresh support from government statistics issued this morning that showed a drop in capacity use in September. But inflation worries have n't been entirely snuffed out on Wall Street, and brokers said investors were looking ahead warily to Friday's scheduled report on the consumer price index for September. Furthermore, just about all market-watchers agree, stocks are likely to be a tough product to sell all week with the anniversary Wednesday of last fall's crash, and all the attendant publicity.
