<HEAD>Chase, Morgan, First Chicago Report Higher 3rd Qtr Profit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Chase </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manhattan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's second-largest banking company, on Monday reported its third-quarter profit jumped 25 percent, while earnings rose 6.6 percent at No. 4-ranked <ORGANIZATION> J.P. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and 80 percent at <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's 11th-largest banker <PERSON> Chase </PERSON> said it earned $ 283 million, or $ 3.09 a share, during the three months ended Sept. 30, up from $ 226 million, or $ 2.55 a share, in the same period a year earlier. For the first three quarters of 1988, <PERSON> Chase </PERSON> said it had earnings of $ 784 million, or $ 8.62 per share, compared with a loss of $ 1.05 billion for the same period last year. The results for the 1987 period included a second-quarter charge of $ 1.6 billion to cover shaky Third World debt. <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> said its third-quarter net income totaled $ 233.6 million, or $ 1.25 a share, up from earnings of $ 219.2 million, or $ 1.18 a share, in the same period a year ago. For the first nine months, the company had a profit of $ 743.7 million, or $ 4 a share, compared with a $ 140.8 million loss in the same period of 1987. The year-earlier results included an $ 875 million loan-loss provision similar to those taken by <PERSON> Chase </PERSON> and other major banks. <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> said its third-quarter profit jumped 80 percent, to $ 111.1 million, or $ 1.73 per share, from $ 61.8 million, or $ 1.05 a share, in the same period of 1987. For the nine-month period, <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> earned a record $ 375.8 million, or $ 6.13 a share, compared with a $ 474.2 million loss last in the first nine months of last year, when it added $ 855 million to its loan-loss reserves. <PERSON> Chase </PERSON> said its third-quarter earnings included an after-tax gain of about $ 103 million from changes in its pension plan. The company said the results also included higher foreign exchange trading income, investment banking fees and trading account gains. The company reported a decline in net interest income because it placed about $ 538 million in credit to Argentine borrowers on nonaccrual status. That means the bank will no longer include on its own statements the interest and other charges due on the loans until the money is actually received. <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> attributed its improved earnings performance partly to higher non-interest operating income, due largely to foreign exchange and trading profits, which more than doubled from a year ago. The company's provision for credit losses of $ 20 million was unchanged from the 1987 quarter. First <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> said its provision for loan losses declined to $ 50 million from $ 75 million a year ago, and that helped improve the earnings picture in the third quarter. `` Our progress ... is shown by the improvement both in capital ratios and in credit quality, where we have the lowest provision for credit losses in four years,'' Chairman <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said in a statement.
