<HEAD>Arthur Andersen Consultants Get Own Identity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Arthur </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Andersen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the largest accounting firm in the nation, announced a new name for its lucrative consulting division Monday in a move thought to be prompted by concerns over ethics and personnel. The change in the division's name _ from <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consulting </ORGANIZATION> to <ORGANIZATION> Andersen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consulting </ORGANIZATION> _ `` creates a clear, separate identity,'' said <PERSON> Duane </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kullberg </PERSON>, managing partner and chief executive officer of the Chicago-based company. <PERSON> Andersen </PERSON>'s consulting service helps businesses tailor computer systems to their specific needs. <PERSON> Andersen </PERSON> launched a study last month to consider a possible restructuring of the entire company, which some observers believe may be a prelude to splitting off consulting as an independent business. The growth of consulting services at major accounting firms has raised questions about the ethics of supposedly objective accounting companies advising their clients on managerial decisions. Some experts have said the ethical problems can only be solved by splitting off consulting as a separate business. Consultants at accounting firms complain that although they are responsible for much of their firms' revenue growth, they are treated and paid as second-class citizens by managing partners who came up through the tax and audit business. The rift has cost <PERSON> Andersen </PERSON> some of its top consulting partners, including four who quit on Friday to join a new consulting venture. The consulting arm of <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Andersen </PERSON> accounts for about 40 percent of the company's total revenue and is growing at a rate of about 30 percent a year, officials said. Consulting fees are expected to total more than $ 1.3 billion at privately held <PERSON> Andersen </PERSON> this year, compared with $ 1.7 billion in revenue from the company's tax and audit portion.
