<HEAD>Two Computer Officials Settle with SEC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two former officials of a computer software company accused of misusing $ 1.1 million from a stock offering to buy securities and a condominium for themselves settled charges with the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Monday. <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Plotkin </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, former chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Intex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Software </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, and his brother, <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Plotkin </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Guttenberg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, a vice president and director of <ORGANIZATION> Intex </ORGANIZATION>, were charged in an <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> civil complaint with making false statements in disclosure documents between May 1986 and February 1987. The complaint, filed in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, says the documents failed to disclose that the <ORGANIZATION> Plotkins </ORGANIZATION> used $ 1.1 million from a stock offering to purchase securities for <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> Plotkin </PERSON> and repay loans that he incurred and to purchase a condominium apartment in <LOCATION> Guttenberg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, for use by <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Plotkin </PERSON>. Without admitting or denying the charges, the brothers agreed to a court order forbidding them from further securities law violations. They were dismissed by <PERSON> Intex </PERSON>' board of directors in March 1987. <PERSON> Awni </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Abboushi </PERSON>, the current president of <ORGANIZATION> Intex </ORGANIZATION>, which is based in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said it was `` heartbreaking'' that the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> was not extracting a financial penalty from the <ORGANIZATION> Plotkins </ORGANIZATION>. He said <PERSON> Intex </PERSON> has sued the brothers for damages and compensation but said the company lacks the money to pursue the suit. <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> assistant director of enforcement, said the <ORGANIZATION> Plotkins </ORGANIZATION> were not charged with using corporate funds for their personal benefit, but rather with failing to disclose the misuse. He said there were no penalties possible under the charges in the complaint. <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Christy </PERSON>, an attorney for the <ORGANIZATION> Plotkins </ORGANIZATION>, said his clients had no comment. <ORGANIZATION> Intex </ORGANIZATION> sells computer word-processing packages that permit the operator to enter text in one or more languages.
